<HEADLINE> National Science &AMP; Technology Week Begins in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The 23rd National Science and
Technology Week began here Sunday to motivate the people to apply
science in daily life and create enthusiasm among the children and
juveniles for innovative works in science and technology.
</P>
<P>
Science and Technology Ministry, jointly with National Science
and Technology Museum, has drawn up a four-day program with the
theme of "Science and Technology for Development" on the occasion,
including science exhibition, seminars and lectures.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating the Week, Finance Minister Shah A.M.S. Kibria
emphasized the need for giving science education priority in the
school level, providing training to science teachers and
establishing science clubs across the country to encourage the new
generation to embrace science era.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the government effort in this regard, the minister
said the present government has taken various measures to develop
science and technology in the country, including duty-free import
of computers and a lump allocation of 150 million taka (2.9
million U.S.dollars) for training computer programmers in the
proposed budget for next fiscal (2000-2001).
</P>
<P>
The government is going to establish 12 science and technology
universities, a biotechnology institute and an information
technology village in the country to meet the demand of the
knowledge economy, Kibria said.
</P>
<P>
Science and Technology Minister Mohammad Noor Uddin Khan said
there is no alternative to science studies to attain sustainable
development of the country, announcing that the government is
going to set up an ocean research institute and a planetarium for
conducting space research. 
</P>
</TEXT>
