<HEADLINE> Japan's Coalition Certain to Secure Majority in Lower House Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Japan's three-way ruling coalition
is certain to secure a combined 241 seats, a simple majority, in
the 480-seat House of Representatives, the Kyodo News Service
reported.
</P>
<P>
The ruling coalition, comprising the Liberal Democratic Party(
LDP), the New Komeito and the New Conservative Party (NCP),
targets a stable majority of 254, which would give it the
chairmanship of all lower house standing committees and at least
the same number of seats on each committee as the opposition.
</P>
<P>
Japan Broadcasting Corp. (NHK), meanwhile, said the three
parties are certain to secure a stable majority.
</P>
<P>
As of 0:47 a.m., the LDP won 225 seats, while the New Komeito
garnered 27 and the NCP 7.
</P>
<P>
Senior LDP officials said Sunday night that Prime Minister
Yoshiro Mori would continue serving as premier only if the ruling
bloc gets a majority. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
