<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Washington to Urge U.S. Companies to Invest in Jordan: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. Deputy Secretary of
Treasury Stuart Eizenstat said Monday that Washington will try to
persuade U.S. companies to step up their investments in Jordan as
the two countries are looking forward to closer economic ties.
</P>
<P>
He made the pledge in talks with Jordanian Prime Minister Ali
Abu Ragheb on trade and economic cooperation between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Eizenstat commended Jordan`s efforts to establish qualified
industrial zones which enabled its entrepreneurs to export products
to U.S. markets, and to create more jobs for the kingdom, where
unemployment rate stands at over 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
Eizenstat also praised the efforts by Jordanian King Abdullah
Bin Hussein to promote peace talks between Israel and its Arab
neighbors as well as Jordanian government's pursuit for higher
economic growth by way of economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
The kingdom is eyeing for a 3 percent economic growth this year
from 1.5 percent in 1999, apparently emerging from a decade-old
economic recession since the 1990 Gulf Crisis.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Ragheb said his government was keen to forge ahead
with economic and administrative reforms to create appropriate
investment conditions for both domestic and foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
Eizenstat said in statement earlier in the day that the U.S. and
Jordan had entered a new era of economic cooperation, and a
historic free trade agreement will soon be discussed between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
Washington has provided Jordan some 1 billion U.S. dollars in
economic and military aid during the past three years.
</P>
<P>
Washington considers Jordan as an important ally in the Arab
world. Their bilateral trade rose drastically from 7.77 million
dollars in 1998 to 325 million dollars in 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
