<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Envoy in Cyprus to Prepare for New Round of Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Alfred Moses, U.S. presidential
emissary for Cyprus, started on Monday a three-day visit to Cyprus
to prepare the ground for the third round of U.N.-sponsored talks
on Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival at the Larnaca airport on Cyprus' southern
coast, Moses underlined the need for compromise on both sides of
the island.
</P>
<P>
"What we need is the art of compromise -- that's the purpose of
negotiations, and that's why the parties are going to Geneva on
July 5," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Negotiation is never a 'sum-zero' game where one side receives
all and the other side nothing," he added.
</P>
<P>
According to Cyprus News Agency, Moses, who is accompanied by
State Department Cyprus coordinator Tomas Weston, will have
separate meetings with Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides and
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek and Turkish Cypriot
communities since 1974 when Turkish invaded and occupied the
northern third of the Mediterranean island in the wake of a failed
pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
Clerides and Denktash have held two rounds of indirect talks
under the United Nations' auspices in an effort to pave the way for
substantive negotiations leading to a comprehensive settlement on
the Cyprus issue. However, no significant progress has been made.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriot side has been demanding that the talks be
aimed to set up a confederation of two states in Cyprus, contrary
to U.N. resolutions and two agreements reached between the two
sides in the 1970s stipulating for a bizonal, bicommunal
federation.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government rejects the idea and sticks to the
resolving of the Cyprus issue under the bizonal, bicommunal
formula.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriot side declared in 1983 a breakaway state in
northern Cyprus, recognized only by Ankara. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
