<DOCNO> XIE20000626.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Announces Budget Surplus Forecast of 1.87 Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton on
Monday predicted the U.S. budget surplus will reach 1.87 trillion
U.S. dollars over the next decade and offered to use some of the
money to cut taxes for married couples if Congress enacts a
prescription drug benefit for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
The budget projection, one trillion dollars higher than
estimated for the 2001-2010 period four months ago, provides a
windfall that the Democratic White House and the Republican-led
Congress are already fighting over ahead of the November 7
election.
</P>
<P>
The White House said the huge increase in the projected surplus,
which was forecast at 746 billion dollars in February, reflected
the booming U.S. economy, and it also boosted growth forecasts for
this year and next.
</P>
<P>
In presenting the figures, Clinton dangled the carrot of 250
billion dollars in tax relief to reduce the so-called "marriage
penalty" paid by two-income married couples, a long-standing
Republican goal, if Congress approved an elderly prescription drug
benefit of roughly the same size.
</P>
<P>
While crowing over the new surplus forecasts, Clinton cautioned
that the money might not actually materialize and argued that the
government should therefore not commit to spending all of it or
return all of it to the public through tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
"I believe it would be a big mistake to commit this entire
surplus to spending or to tax cuts," he said. "The projections
could be wrong, they could be right. That's why we shouldn't spend
it all now."
</P>
<P>
The new 1.87-trillion-dollar surplus projection excluded Social
Security. With Social Security's own surpluses included, the
overall 10-year black ink was being projected at 4.19 trillion
dollars, a Democratic official said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton wants to save the entire Social Security surplus of 2.3
trillion dollars over 10 years and devote it to paying down the
public debt.
</P>
<P>
The White House said that the new budget projections, and the
dedication of some of the new surplus to debt reduction, would
allow the government to pay off its debt by 2012, a year earlier
than forecast in February.
</P>
<P>
Of the 5.7-trillion-dollar national debt, Clinton would pay off
the 3.5 trillion dollars held by the public. The remaining 2.2
trillion dollars is money the government owes its own trust funds
for Social Security and other programs.
</P>
<P>
Vice President Al Gore wants a 500-billion-dollar tax cut and
more spending for Social Security, health, schools and the
environment.
</P>
<P>
George W. Bush, the presumed Republican nominee for president,
wants to use 1.3 trillion dollars of the surplus for a tax cut and
more of it for debt reduction and shoring up Social Security.
</P>
<P>
The fresh projections were put forward as part of the annual
midsession review of the budget, which also forecast stronger
growth than predicted in February as well as higher inflation than
previously expected.
</P>
<P>
The review predicted gross domestic product growth at 3.9
percent this year and 3.2 percent next, up from the 2.9 percent
and 2.6 percent predicted with the February budget submission.
</P>
<P>
The Consumer Price Index, on a fourth quarter to fourth quarter
basis, was forecast at 3.2 percent in 2000, up from the 2.3
percent estimated in February. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000626.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Firmly Against Arms Sales to Taiwan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 26 (Xinhua) -- China said here Monday that
it is firmly opposed to the attempt by certain countries to make
arms sales to Taiwan, a Chinese province, saying that such sales
not only jeopardizes China's sovereignty and security, but also
poses a threat to the peace and security in Asia and Pacific.
</P>
<P>
The statement came as Shen Guofang, deputy Chinese permanent
representative to the United Nations, took the floor at the
plenary meeting of the United Nations Disarmament Commission (UNDC)
, which opened here Monday and will end in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
"China is firmly opposed to the attempts by certain countries
to undermine the sovereignty and territorial integrity of other
countries by means of arms sales," Shen said.
</P>
<P>
"Taiwan is an inalienable part of China," he said. "This has
been recognized by the international community."
</P>
<P>
"However, certain countries, in disregard of this fact, have
been selling large amount of advanced weapons to Taiwan," he said.
"This action violates the principle of respecting national
sovereignty and territorial integrity as enshrined in the U.N.
Charter."
</P>
<P>
"It not only jeopardizes China's sovereignty and security, but
also poses a threat to the peace and stability in the Asia-Pacific
region," he said.
</P>
<P>
This goes against the spirit of the confidence-building
measures (CBMs), and "We demand countries concerned stop this
wrong practice as soon as possible," he added.
</P>
<P>
China is of the view that there is only one China in the world,
the Government of the People's Republic of China is the only
legitimate government of China, representing all Chinese,
including people in Taiwan, and Taiwan is an inalienable part of
China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
