<HEADLINE> EU Stresses Condemnation of Violence in Zimbabwe's Pre-election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The European Union Election
Observer Mission Monday said violence and intimidation during the
pre-election period in Zimbabwe must be condemned.
</P>
<P>
Head of the EU mission Pierre Schori said in an interim report
that serious defects in the electoral process, particularly in
regard to the voters' roll and lack of transparency of the
electoral authorities, must be resolved.
</P>
<P>
He said the presence of international observers had a calming
and stabilizing effect.
</P>
<P>
The overall assessment of the polling, he said, was highly
positive with presiding officers and their staff competent and
efficient.
</P>
<P>
He said there were serious problems with the voters' roll, and
as a result a number of eligible voters were unable to cast their
ballots.
</P>
<P>
Political Adviser to the ruling Zimbabwe African National
Front-Patriotic Front (Zanu-pf) Jonathan Moyo dismissed the EU's
assessment, saying it was not representative of the international
community.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 people were killed in the run-up to the fifth
parliamentary elections in which more than 4 million of the 5.1
million registered voters cast their votes on Saturday and Sunday.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
