<HEADLINE> Iranian Opposition Leader Detained for Attending Berlin Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRNA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- A prominent Iranian opposition
leader was detained on Monday by the Islamic revolution court for
attending a controversial political conference on Iran in Germany
in April.
</P>
<P>
Branch 3 of the Islamic revolution court in Tehran issued
temporary arrest warrant for Ezzatollah Sahabi, member of the
Freedom Movement of Iran (FMI), for taking part in the Berlin
conference, Tehran Justice Department was quoted by the Islamic
Republic News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
The department said Sahabi was summoned to court for questioning
about the classified letters found from the houses of some
participants of the Berlin conference.
</P>
<P>
Sahabi was suspected of having links with other participants in
the Berlin conference, it said.
</P>
<P>
Sahabi, a supporter of the reformist policies of President
Mohammad Khatami, had been summoned to court for attending the
conference, held on April 7-9 by the German Heinrich Boell
Foundation, on Iran after the February parliamentary elections. But
he was set free on bail then.
</P>
<P>
Iran's powerful conservatives have strongly condemned the
conference, attended by a dozen reformist allies of Khatami, as "
anti-Islamic" and accused the reformists of advocating "U.S.-style
reforms in Iran," which the supreme leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei
strongly rejected.
</P>
<P>
The conservative-dominated courts have arrested at least six
participants of the conference but released some of them on bail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
