<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Says Two Civilians Injured in U.S.-British Air Raids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Two Iraqi civilians were injured
when U.S. and British warplanes bombed civilian installations in
southern Iraq Sunday morning, a military spokesman.
</P>
<P>
In a statement carried by the official Iraqi News Agency (INA),
the spokesman said that at 8:45 (0445 GMT) on Sunday, U.S. and
British planes bombed targets inside the southern Thi-Qar province.
</P>
<P>
The two injured, identified as 10-year-old Yasamein Aoda Aziz
and 18-year-old Hashimia Aoda Aziz, were taken to a nearby hospital
for emergency treatment, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Thi-Qar province is one of the seven provinces covered in the
southern no-fly zone, set up by the U.S.-led Western allies after
the 1991 Gulf War with the claimed aim of protecting the Shiite
Muslims from persecution of the troops of Iraqi President Saddam
Hussein.
</P>
<P>
A similar air exclusion zone was also set up in northern Iraq to
allegedly protect the Kurds population there.
</P>
<P>
Iraq says the zones, which were not specifically authorized by
the United Nations, violate its national sovereignty. It has been
challenging the patrols since December 1998, when the United States
and Britain launched the Operation Desert Fox air strikes against
Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
