<HEADLINE> UAE Keen to Help Iraqi People: Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, June 26 (Xinhua) -- A major daily of the United Arab
Emirates on Monday commented on the reopening of Iraq's embassy
here, saying that the step was a reciprocal one which indicates the
UAE has great concern "over the plight of Iraqi people."
</P>
<P>
There was a dire need to help the innocent Iraqi people, who are
suffering from the U.N. sanctions imposed after Iraq's 1990
invasion of neighboring Iraq, said the Dubai-based "Gulf News."
</P>
<P>
The paper pointed out that more than 2 million people, including
half a million children, have reportedly lost their lives as a
result of the sanctions, adding the UAE was one of a growing number
of countries that are demanding a lifting of these crippling
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
This necessitates an open diplomatic channel in order to
facilitate humanitarian assistance for them, the paper said, with
the proper establishment of relations with Iraq, the UAE will prove
its commitment to aiding Iraqi people in need.
</P>
<P>
The UAE reopened its embassy in Baghdad on April 20, ending a
decade of diplomatic freeze. Iraq is to reopen its embassy here in
the coming few days, according to the official WAM news agency.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's acting charge d'affaires, Abdul Razak Hamoudi Ahmed,
presented his letter of credentials to UAE Foreign Ministry's
Undersecretary Saif Saeed bin Saed here on June 24. 
</P>
<P>
The paper said UAE President Sheikh Zayed Bin Sultan Al-Nahyan
was one of the first leaders to call for the lifting of sanctions,
because they were hurting the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
It is no surprise that the UAE has been in the forefront of
humanitarian aid to Iraq to help the population, which has been hit
hard by sanctions and by American and British bombings, the paper
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
