<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Anti-drug Regional Meeting Held in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Deputy Secretary General Pino
Arlacchi on Monday called on Western and Central Asian countries
to "urgently" start a campaign against the production and
trafficking of drugs, which have reached a "dangerous level".
</P>
<P>
Arlacchi, also the executive director of the U.N. Office for
Drug Control and Crime Prevention, made the appeal in a statement
at a meeting on regional drugs problems, held by the U.N.
Subcommission for Drugs Trafficking and Related Problems in the
Near and Middle East, Turkey's Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of 30 regional countries and of countries and
international organizations in observers' status participated in
the meeting, which kicked off Monday in Antalya in southern Turkey
to run through June 30.
</P>
<P>
Arlacchi noted that opium production in Afghanistan, a major
opium producer of the world, had reached a record level of 4,600
tons annually. Moreover, the volatile Central Asian country has
also been able to produce heroin recently.
</P>
<P>
Pointing out that drugs and crimes go hand in hand, Arlacchi
underlined the fact that farmers accepting to produce raw material
for drugs often become bound by illegal organizations and terrorist
groups.
</P>
<P>
He said terrorist groups usually spend the income of drug
smuggling on the purchase of weapons.
</P>
<P>
About 60-80 percent of the drugs smuggled to the European
continent was supplied by or transported via Central Asia,
participants of the meeting said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Iran are of major importance in the fight against
this crime due to their significant geographical locations on the
drug trafficking routes.
</P>
<P>
During the five-day meeting, the participants are expected to
discuss ways to increase cooperation against the smuggling of
narcotics, measures that governments have to take against this
crime and means to prevent corruption and money laundering.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
