<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE Takes First in Economic Growth Among GCC Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The economic growth of the United
Arab Emirates (UAE) in 1999 reached four percent, topping the Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) countries, said a report issued Monday by
the Muscat-based Gulf Organization for Industrial Consultancy
(GOIC).
</P>
<P>
The other GCC countries also witnessed a notable improvement in
their gross domestic product (GDP), due to the rise of oil prices
in the world market, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The UAE was followed by Oman with 3.7 percent growth in GDP,
Bahrain with 3.2 percent, Saudi Arabia with 1.8 percent, Qatar with
1.3 percent and Kuwait with 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a report issued recently by the Emirates' central
bank said that the UAE's GDP rose in 1999 to 190 billion dirhams
(51.9 billion U.S. dollars). 
</P>
<P>
The report attributed the rise to the increase in the revenues
of crude and manufacturing industries. 
</P>
<P>
Non-oil products contributed 147 billion dirhams (40.16 billion
dollars), or 74.4 percent of the GDP, whereas it contributed 137
billion dirhams (37.43 billion US dollars), or 79.2 percent, in
1998.
</P>
<P>
The country's per capital income increased by 3.9 percent from
62,400 dirhams (17,049.18 dollars) in 1998 to 64,800 dirhams (17,
704.92 dollars) in 1999. 
</P>
<P>
The surplus in trade balance surged from only 2 billion dirhams
(546.45 million dollars) in 1998 to 12.4 billion dirhams (3.3
billion dollars) in 1999 due to the rise of the dirham exchange
rate against currencies of all UAE's leading trade partners, except
Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
