<HEADLINE> UAE to Set up World's First Free Zone for Internet, E-commerce Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Dubai Internet City (DIC) in
the United Arab Emirates (UAE) will be the first free zone in the
world for internet and e-commerce companies, which will enjoy 100
percent ownership, tax free income and 50-year lease of land.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed bin Rashid al Maktoum, crown prince of Dubai, told
reporters in Dubai on Monday that he is ready to make utmost
efforts for the project.
</P>
<P>
DIC boasts offices for international IT companies, e-commerce
centers, software development centers and the first internet
university in the world as well as permanent showrooms for internet
and e-commerce technology.
</P>
<P>
The value of consumer goods in e-commerce is estimated at 40
billion U.S. dollars now and is expected to reach 150 billion
dollars in two years, while the e-commerce among companies stood at
30 billion dollars and is expected to rise to one trillion dollars
in the next three to four years, said Maktoum.
</P>
<P>
DIC has issued licences for more than 100 local, regional and
international IT companies to run their business in the city, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The Crown Prince believed that the UAE had "the capability to
convert dreams into reality" and that DIC will be an opportunity
for the UAE to "take a leading position in the world of information
technology".  
</P>
</TEXT>
