<HEADLINE> Canada, EU Agree on Peace-Building, International Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Canada and the European Union (EU)
have reached agreements on peace-building and international trade,
Canadian Minister Jean Chretien said in an announcement released
here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The announcement followed the Canada-EU summit held Monday in
Lisbon, Portugal, between Chretien and his Portuguese counterpart
Antonio Guterres, who assumes the Presidency of the European
Council,and President of the European Commission Romano Prodi.
</P>
<P>
The Canada-EU Joint Statement on Peace Building and Conflict
Prevention commits the two sides to meet within six months on
peace-building and conflict prevention, as well as on small arms
and light weapons, civil wars and corporate social responsibility,
the government announcement stated.
</P>
<P>
In the Canada-EU Joint Statement on the World Trade
Organization,the two sides expressed support for the launch of a
new trade Round that would reflect the "balanced interests of all
WTO members."
</P>
<P>
The two sides said their aim is "to further liberalize
international trade, facilitate the integration of developing
countries into the global economy and take into account
sustainable development, consumer health and cultural diversity."
</P>
</TEXT>
