<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Announce Completion of Working Draft of Human Genome </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Scientists involved in the publicly funded Human Genome Project
and at the private company Celera Genomics Inc., announced the
historic achievement, which is regarded as important as an man's
walking on the moon. The announcement was made at the Capitol
Hilton Hotel at Washington.
</P>
<P>
Francis Collins, chief scientist of the Human Genome Project,
which was launched in 1990, said that they have completed a "
working draft" of the human genome, which contains the genetic
sequence of an estimated 90 percent of the sequence arranged in
near perfect order on a genetic map.
</P>
<P>
Craig Venter, president and chief science officer of Celera
said scientists of his company has assembled the 3.5 billion
letters of genetic code into their natural order.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton, joined at the White House
announcement by British Prime Minister Tony Blair, hailed
completion of the work, calling it "a day for the ages."
</P>
<P>
The genetic blueprint of the human body is like a string of
letters representing the four substances that make up every gene:
adenine, thymine, guanine and cystosine, referred to simply as A,
T, G and C.
</P>
<P>
Scientists said that knowing the sequence of letters that make
up all DNA in humans opens an era in which the most fundamental
causes of disease can be understood and targeted treatments can be
developed.
</P>
<P>
The Human Genome Project is an international consortium
supported mostly by the U.S. National Institutes of Health and the
Wellcome Trust, a philanthropic organization based in London.
Celera Genomics Inc. is a private company based in Rockville,
Maryland.
</P>
<P>
The ten-year effort involved thousands of scientists from
United States, Britain, Germany, Japan, France and China and cost
nearly three billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
After completing the draft map of human chromosomes, scientists
will turn their work to annotation: learning the function of every
gene and how genes relate to one another.
</P>
<P>
"The real work begins," Dr. Francis Collins said. "There is a
very long list of things that we can do, all of which will greatly
benefit medicine."
</P>
<P>
Scientists believe eventually medicine will be able to identify
from birth the diseases that a person may develop and to provide
treatment to extend life and health beyond what was ever possible
before. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000626.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
