<HEADLINE> Russia to Hike Oil Export Duties As of August 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Russian government has decided
to increase export duties on crude oil from 20 to 27 euros per ton
as of August 1, Russian Deputy Prime Minister Viktor Khristenko
announced here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The governmental commission on protective measures in foreign
trade and on customs and tariff policy has adopted a decision to
hike export duties on crude and fuel oil as of August 1 this year,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The export duty on Russian oil will be raised from 20 to 27
euros per ton. If the price of oil on the world market climbs
higher than 29 per barrel before the end of June, the duty may go
up to 34 euros per ton as of August 1, Khristenko said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said the export duty on Russian fuel oil will be
increased from 12 to 20 euros per ton. 
</P>
</TEXT>
