<HEADLINE> Fiat, GM Make Joint Offer For Korea's Car-Maker Daewoo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Fiat and General Motors, the two car-
makers who linked up in March, are to make a joint bid for the
South Korean auto firm Daewoo, Fiat sources said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The bid, which was presented Monday, entails the creation of a
new company whose shareholding structure has not yet been hammered
out,Italian news agency quoted sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
But GM would hold a majority, Fiat would have up to 20 percent
and the remainder would be split among Daewoo creditors and other
interested parties.
</P>
<P>
The new company would take over the ownership and management of
all the South Korean activities of Daewoo and its Sanggyong unit,
as well as the majority of its international activities.
</P>
<P>
On March 13 this year, GM and Fiat announced a deal in which
the U.S. giant would take 20 percent of Fiat's car division and
Fiat would take 5 percent of GM, the world's largest car-maker.
</P>
</TEXT>
