<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BoE Warns On Risk Of Corporate Failure In UK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The financial health of Britain's
least profitable companies is weaker now than it was during the
last recession, according to new Bank of England research.
</P>
<P>
The research, carried in the Bank's Financial Stability Review,
reached its conclusions after a wide ranging study of some 1200
quoted companies operating in all sectors of the economy in the
period 1974-98.
</P>
<P>
It showed while the top 10 percent of highly geared companies
have seen gearing surge to levels not seen for at least a quarter
of a century, serious structural weaknesses are emerging at the
other end.
</P>
<P>
The research found that profitability for the weaker firms is
lower now than at any time in the last 25 year.Even worse, many
companies are burdened with heavy borrowings.
</P>
<P>
"Despite the broadly favorable outlook for the corporate sector
as a whole, the least profitable companies in 1998 were much less
profitable than the least-profitable companies in the recessions
of the early 1980s and early 1990s," the research concluded.
</P>
<P>
It added: "These results imply that the downside risks facing
creditors of the corporate sector may have been greater in recent
years than suggested by aggregate corporate performance alone."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
