<HEADLINE> United Nations Disarmament Commission Starts Plenary Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Disarmament Commission (UNDC) Monday kicked off the plenary
meeting at a time when the United States is pressing hard for the
future deployment of the National Missile Defense system.
</P>
<P>
The event, which lasts two weeks, is the first UNDC plenary
meeting of the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
Opening the meeting, Jayantha Dhanapala, U.N. under-sceretary-
general for disarmament affairs, said, "The fist issue on this
year's agenda concerns ways and means to achieve nuclear
disarmament."
</P>
<P>
"Circumstances should be favorable for additional progress in
this area," he said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting came when most of the countries have voiced their
dissatisfaction with the slow progress in the nuclear disarmament
by the two most powerful nuclear weapons states, the United States
and Russia, who hold the largest nuclear arsenals in the world.
