<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Takes Measures To Deal With Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Police Commissioner
Augustine Chihuri Monday appealed to Zimbabweans to remain calm
and not to speculate on the election results.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters at the press conference here that enough
police had been deployed throughout the country to maintain law
and order.
</P>
<P>
"Some people may become over-excited and start spreading
rumors, causing problems," he said, adding: "We have deployed
enough police to ensure that those who do not accept the outcome
of the election are forced to do so."
</P>
<P>
Chief Superintendent Wayne Bvudzijena said that they have put
in place contingency security measures countrywide to deal with
any form of post- election violence which may occur after the
announcement of the parliamentary election results.
</P>
<P>
He said that police had mounted road blocks at Harare's major
roads to prevent the bussing of political supporters who may
trigger violence while celebrating.
</P>
<P>
"We are not sure of what the situation will be like after the
election results are announced," he said. "Groups of more than
10 people will be dispersed. The situation is still calm as of
now."
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe held the fifth Parliamentary election from June 24 to
25.
</P>
<P>
At least 30 people were killed countrywide in political
violence in the run-up to the election. 
</P>
