<HEADLINE> Irish Court Postpones Trial of Former PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- An Irish court on Monday ordered to
postpone the trial of former Irish prime minister Charles Haughey
on charges of obstructing a government inquiry into payments to
politicians.
</P>
<P>
In Dublin, the capital city of Ireland, a Criminal Court judge
said there was a real or substantial risk that Haughey would not
receive a fair trial, a Reuters report from Dublin quoted the
Irish state broadcaster as saying.
</P>
<P>
Haughey, 74, who served as Irish prime minister four times
between 1979 and 1992, is accused of obstructing the 1997
McCracken Tribunal into payments to politicians from businessmen.
</P>
<P>
It is accused that Haughey received some 1.3 million Irish
pounds(about 1.54 million U.S.dollars) in donations from a tycoon
friend between 1987 and 1991.
</P>
<P>
However, it was concluded that there did not appear to be any
political impropriety relating to the payments on the part of
Haughey.
</P>
<P>
Tribunals are being widely used to probe corruption allegations
in Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Headed by a senior judge, they have the power to force
witnesses to give evidence and ultimately produce a report and
recommendations which can then give rise to civil or criminal
proceedings.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
