<DOCNO> XIE20000626.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Existing Home Sales Rebound in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Sales of existing homes posted
a surprise 4.3 percent increase in May following a 6.2 percent
decrease in the previous month, the National Association of
Realtors reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The May advance pushed existing-home sales to a seasonally
adjusted annual rate of 5.09 million units from a rate of 4.88
million sales in April, suggesting that despite rising interest
rates, the housing market remains strong.
</P>
<P>
Housing analysts said the strength in May in part reflected the
fact that more homes than normal were put on the market in March
and April after strong demand in earlier months had pushed the
inventory of unsold homes to a record low.
</P>
<P>
"Many buyers were frustrated in early spring because there
simply weren't enough homes on the market," said Dennis R. Cronk,
the president of the Realtors group. "Many homes listed in March
and April received quick offers, resulting in a higher number of
transactions closed in May."
</P>
<P>
The sales jump came as a surprise to many economists who had
been expecting home resales would be unchanged or even dip
slightly as the housing market cooled under the impact of six
interest rate increases over the past year by the Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
The central bank was scheduled to meet Tuesday and Wednesday
with economists predicting Fed officials will decide to leave
rates unchanged this time, preferring to wait to see if the rate
increases already implemented will work as intended to slow
economic activity enough to keep inflation in check.
</P>
<P>
For May, sales were up in all regions of the country, led by a
7.5 percent rise in the Midwest, where home resales climbed to an
annual rate of 1.15 million units.
</P>
<P>
Sales were up 3.9 percent in the West to an annual rate of 1.34
million units. In the South, sales rose 3.6 percent to an annual
rate of 1.99 million units and the Northeast saw sales rise by 1.7
percent to an annual rate of 610,000 units.
</P>
<P>
The median sales price, the price where half the homes sold for
more and half for less, was 137,200 U.S. dollars in May, up 3.3
percent from April. The average sales price rose by 5.5 percent to
176,600 dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
