<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, June 26 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- A publicly funded project and a private research
center are to announce here on Monday noon that they have finished
decoding the human genome -- a milestone in the exploration of
life.
</P>
<P>
Scientists involved in the publicly funded Human Genome Project
and at the private company Celera Genomics Inc., are to announce
the historic achievement, which is regarded as important as an
man's walking on the moon. The announcement will be made at the
Capitol Hilton Hotel in Washington.
</P>
<P>
Francis Collins, chief scientist of the Human Genome Project,
which was launched in 1990, said before the announcement that they
have completed a "working draft" of the human genome, which
contains the genetic sequence of an estimated 90 percent of the
sequence arranged in near perfect order on a genetic map. (US-
Human Genome)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- The Organization for Economic Cooperation and
Development (OECD) Monday threatened to impose sanctions against
35 tax havens, some of them closely linked with France, Britain
and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The OECD accused these tax havens of practicing a "prejudicial
tax competition" by seeking to attract banking deposits from
individuals and companies who want to avoid paying taxes in their
own countries.
</P>
<P>
The tax havens on the OECD list include the British Virgin
Islands, Cook Islands, Marshall Islands, the U.S. Virgin Islands
and Vanuatu. (OECD-Sanctions-Tax Havens)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
GENEVA -- The United Nations General Assembly (UNGA) began a
week-long special session here Monday to address social
development issues amidst the heightened concern over such social
issues as poverty, employment and worker rights in the age of
globalization.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, Danish Prime Minister Poul
Nyrup Rasmussen, Swiss President Adolf Ogi, and Chinese Vice
Premier Wen Jiabao were among more than 100 heads of state and
heads of delegations and observers present at the opening session.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the special session is to advance the global social
development agenda that was set at the 1995 World Summit for
Social Development (Social Summit) in Copenhagen, Denmark,
according to a U.N. press release. (UN-Social Development)
</P>
</TEXT>
