<HEADLINE> No Death Penalty for Accused Iranian Jews: Iranian Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Head of the Justice Department of
Iran's southern Fars Province Hossein Ali Amiri said on Monday that
the 13 Iranian Jews accused of espionage for Israel will not face
the death penalty, and the final verdict for them is expected on
July 1.
</P>
<P>
The defendants are only accused of "acts against the national
security" and the charge of "mohareb" (waging war against God and
the country) has been dropped, hence they would not face the
capital punishment, the official announced, actually repeating what
he said last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
His remarks contradict those of Prosecutor-General Ayatollah
Morteza Moghtadai who said on Sunday that the accused may receive
the death penalty since they have confessed to spying for Israel.
</P>
<P>
The final verdict will be issued on July 1, which will involve
the 13 Jews along with four Muslims charged with the same offenses,
Amiri was quoted by the Islamic Republic News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
Altogether eight Muslims have been accused of spying, but Amiri
said the case for the other four of them is not over yet.
</P>
<P>
He referred to the likelihood of some of the accused being
acquitted, saying that it depends on the decision of the presiding
judge.
</P>
<P>
Court hearings for the accused Jews started on April 13 in
Shiraz, capital of Fars Province. So far at least eight of them
have reportedly confessed to passing on classified information to
Israel and having connections with Israel's security service.
</P>
<P>
The 13 Jews were arrested in Shiraz in March 1999. Resisting
Western pressure to release them, Iran has maintained their arrest
had nothing to do with their religious background and no foreign
countries should interfere in Iran's internal affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
