<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore's All Business Community Sectors to Be United </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 26 (Xinhua) -- All sectors of business
community in Singapore will soon be united in a single federation,
according to Singapore Minister for Trade and Industry George Yeo.
</P>
<P>
Delivering a speech at the Singapore Federation of Chambers of
Commerce and Industry (SFCCI) Annual Luncheon Monday, Yeo said
that SFCCI has taken a bold move and decided to create the
Singapore Business Federation (SBF) which will represent
Singapore's private sector, both locally and abroad.
</P>
<P>
He said the decision was made in line with Prime Minister Goh
Chok Tong's suggestion to transform the SFCCI into the apex
representative body of the private sector in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
"The government therefore welcomes your plan to restructure
SFCCI and strengthen it," Yeo said, adding "A strong business
federation will articulate more effectively the needs of
entrepreneurs in Singapore, big and small."
</P>
<P>
On the role SBF will play, Yeo said that SBF will represent
Singapore in the international arena and to speak for the entire
business community in Singapore with one voice when dealing with
the government.
</P>
<P>
According to Yeo's paraphrase, Domestically, SBF should help
to strengthen the links between government and the private sector,
improve further the pro-enterprise environment, play a role in
shaping national plans, provide enterprises with better support
services and help them to improve their business practices.
</P>
<P>
Abroad, SBF should strengthen Singapore's links with other
governments and business communities through bilateral exchanges
and participation in multilateral forum. In addition, it should
enlist the help of its multinational company members to expand
Singapore's business interest overseas and take the lead in
representing Singapore's private sector at multilateral forums.
</P>
<P>
On funding to the need of SBF, Yeo said the collection of an
annual levy from the top companies in Singapore has been proposed.
</P>
<P>
"The proposal for the business levy to be limited to the top 5
to 10 percent of companies in Singapore, on some kind of scale, so
as not to burden the smaller enterprises, is a reasonable one," he
added.
</P>
<P>
SFCCI, which currently is a low-profile and low-budget body,
groups the Singapore International Chamber of Commerce and the
country's four ethnic-based chambers, namely the Singapore Chinese
Chamber of Commerce &AMP; Industry, the Singapore Indian Chamber of
Commerce &AMP; Industry, the Singapore Malay Chamber of Commerce &AMP;
Industry and Singapore Confederation of Industries.
</P>
<P>
When SFCCI becomes the new boy, it will take within its ambit
powerful groups that had gone their own independent ways, such as
the Singapore National Employers Federation, Association of Banks
in Singapore and Real Estate Developers Association of Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Two other leading business associations, the Singapore Shipping
Association and the Singapore information Technology Federation,
are also expected to be among the SBF's 10 founding members.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000626.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
