<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inspectors Satisfied over IRA Arms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Two international statesmen
appointed to inspect Irish Republican Arms (IRA) arms dumps said
on Monday that they were satisfied that weapons have been secured.
</P>
<P>
In a report to Northern Ireland's International Independent
Decommissioning Commission, Cyril Ramaphosa and Martti Ahtisaari
said they have been "shown a substantial quantity of IRA arms,
including explosives".
</P>
<P>
They added they "have ensured the weapons are secure and cannot
be used without their becoming aware that this has happened".
</P>
<P>
The two men met British Prime Minister Tony Blair in Downing
Street on Monday morning to update him on what they had seen.
</P>
<P>
After their meeting,Blair said the inspections represented "a
very substantial further step along the road to a lasting peace".
</P>
<P>
He added that although there was still a long way to go in the
political process, Northern Ireland "has never had a better
prospect than it has had today".
</P>
<P>
The inspections report was presented after the IRA released a
statement on Monday saying some of its arms dumps had been
inspected and it had renewed contact with the decommissioning body.
</P>
<P>
The inspectors said in their report: "All our requests were
satisfactorily met. We plan to re-inspect the arms dumps on a
regular basis to ensure that the weapons have remained secure."
</P>
<P>
"The process that led to the first inspection visit and the way
in which it was carried out makes us believe that this is a
genuine effort by the IRA to advance the peace process," they
added.
</P>
<P>
In its statement, the IRA said that the dumps inspected"
contained a substantial amount of material including weapons,
explosives and other equipment".
</P>
<P>
The IRA agreed in May to allow the two international inspectors
to verify that some of their arms dumps were secure as part of the
package of proposals to reinstate Northern Ireland devolution and
the power-sharing executive.
</P>
<P>
Former Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari and South Africa's
former Secretary General of the African National Congress (ANC)
Cyril Ramaphosa were appointed as the international arms
inspectors to report to the decommissioning body headed by
Canadian General John de Chastelain.
</P>
<P>
In its latest statement the IRA said: "On May 6th the
leadership of the IRA announced an unprecedented initiative which
had the effect of breaking the impasse at that time in the peace
process."
</P>
<P>
"The leadership of the IRA have consistently sought to enhance
the peace process. This initiative demonstrates once more our
commitment to securing a just and lasting peace," it added.
</P>
<P>
Northern Ireland's First Minister and Ulster Unionist leader
David Trimble has said there would be "a serious problem" and"
consequences" if the IRA did not make a gesture on weapons soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000626.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Peacekeepers in Kosovo Accused of Theft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- British Ministry of Defense said on
Monday that four British peacekeepers in Yugoslavia have been
accused of stealing money and valuables from ethnic Albanian
civilians at a checkpoint in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The four soldiers, on duty in the international peacekeeping
force in the southern Yugoslav province of kosovo, have been
separated and assigned to other duties.
</P>
<P>
"Because it was a four-man patrol and an allegation was made
that money and effects were stolen, they are all under
investigation," a spokesman in the defense ministry said.
</P>
<P>
"But we don't know yet whether it's one or more that actually
are being accused," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the soldiers "would be dealt with quite severely"
if the allegations proved true.
</P>
<P>
The Albanian civilians claimed that the soldiers took mobile
phones, cameras and up to 10,000 pounds (about 15,000 U.S. dollars)
worth of Deutschemarks at a checkpoint in Pristina, the provincial
capital of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The Military Police special investigation branch was looking
into the case, the spokesman added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
