<HEADLINE> S. African Revenue Services Fail to Erase Gap in Financial Records </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESUBR, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The South African Revenue
Services (SARS) remains unable to reconcile a discrepancy of 413
million rand (about 61 million U.S. dollars) in its financial
records due to problems in its accounting system.
</P>
<P>
Addressing Parliament's watchdog Public Accounts Committee
(PAC) on Monday, SARS operational manager Andrew Fisher said the
funds could only be reconciled once the problems were corrected.
</P>
<P>
If the funds were found to have arisen from an over-collection
of taxes, the taxpayers would be refunded, Fishe was quoted by the
South African Press Association as saying.
</P>
<P>
The funds would remain in SARS' bank account until that stage.
</P>
<P>
SARS has blamed the discrepancy on problems associated with the
 organizations transformation from a cash to accrual basis of
accounting.
</P>
<P>
PAC's chairman Gavin Woods expressed concern at SARS' apparent
 inability to cope with the transformation of its systems.
</P>
<P>
"The non-compliance of basic accounting principles... indicates
gross financial irresponsibility," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said it was not acceptable that all accounting problems be
blamed on the transformation process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
