<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Launches Joint Report on Poverty Reduction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
launched here Monday a joint report by four major international
organizations calling on both developing and industrialized
countries to implement their commitments to attack the root causes
of poverty.
</P>
<P>
"During the 1990s, United Nations world conferences set major
goals for economic and social development," said Annan at a
ceremony in the Palais des Nations. "All countries, developed and
developing alike, signed on to this agenda, often at the highest
political level."
</P>
<P>
He said that the collaborative report, co-authored by the U.N.,
the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development, the
International Monetary Fund, and the World Bank, had provided some
answers to questions including whether the world had made good on
these commitments.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time ever that the four main international
bodies concerned with development have together reviewed progress
towards the internationally agreed goals for reducing extreme
poverty, and have articulated a common vision of the way forward,
according to the U.N. chief.
</P>
<P>
Major points of the report, entitled "A Better World for All,"
include:
</P>
<P>
-- As growth increased in the mid-1990s, the proportion of
people living on less than one U.S. dollar a day fell rapidly in
Asia, but little or not at all in Africa. Income inequality
remains a barrier to progress in Latin America;
</P>
<P>
-- More than 100 million children will not be in school in 2015,
if current trends prevail;
</P>
<P>
-- The gender gap in primary and secondary enrollment is
narrowing, but not fast enough to reach the goal of eliminating
gender disparities in schools by 2005;
</P>
<P>
-- For every country that has decreased infant and under-five
child mortality rates fast enough to reach the goals, 10 lagged
behind and another one moved backwards, often because of HIV/AIDS;
</P>
<P>
-- Skilled care during pregnancy and delivery can do much to
avoid may of the half million maternal deaths each year;
</P>
<P>
-- During the 1990s, the use of contraception increased in all
regions, but Africa lagged behind;
</P>
<P>
-- By 1997, fewer than half the countries in the world had
strategies for environmental sustainability.
</P>
<P>
The major obstacles to success, according to the report, are
inadequate policies, human rights abuses, conflicts, natural
disasters, HIV/AIDS, inequities in come, education and access to
health care, as well as unequal opportunities between men and
women.
</P>
<P>
It also notes that developing countries' efforts to improve
conditions for their citizens are seriously hampered by a lack of
access to global markets, the debt burden, a decline in
development assistance, and inconsistencies in donor policies.
</P>
<P>
Stressing that there is no single solution to achieving the
goals, the report finds that greater commitment from both
developing and developed countries, as well as stronger voices and
more choices for the poor, can make a difference.
</P>
<P>
Economic growth is part of the solution, but not a guarantee in
itself, according to the report. Also important is more
investment in basic social services which can produce greater pay-
offs in terms of development, as well as ensuring that the
benefits of economic progress reach the poorest people.
</P>
<P>
It believes that openness to trade, technology and knowledge,
and the capacity to use it can also stimulate progress for the
poorest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
