<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Working Draft of Human Genome Completed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- A publicly funded project and a
private research center are to announce here on Monday noon that
they have finished decoding the human gonome -- a milestone in the
exploration of life.
</P>
<P>
Scientists involved in the publicly funded Human Genome Project
and at the private company Celera Genomics Inc., are to announce
the historic achievement, which is regarded as important as an
man's walking on the moon. The announcement will be made at the
Capitol Hilton Hotel in Washington.
</P>
<P>
Francis Collins, chief scientist of the Human Genome Project,
which was launched in 1990, said before the announcement that they
have completed a "working draft" of the human genome, which
contains the genetic sequence of an estimated 90 percent of the
sequence arranged in near perfect order on a genetic map.
</P>
<P>
Craig Venter, president and chief science officer of Celera
said scientists of his company has assembled the 3.5 billion
letters of genetic code into their natural order.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, joined at the White House announcement by British
Prime Minister Tony Blair, hailed completion of the work, calling
it "a day for the ages."
</P>
<P>
"Today we are learning the language in which God created life,"
Clinton said, "We are gaining ever more awe for the complexity,
the beauty, the wonder of God's most divine and sacred gift."
</P>
<P>
The Human Genome Project is an international consortium
supported mostly by the U.S. National Institutes of Health and the
Wellcome Trust, a philanthropic organization based in London.
Celera Genomics Inc. is a private company based in Rockville,
Maryland.
</P>
<P>
The 10-year effort involved thousands of scientists from United
States, Britain, Germany, Japan, France and China and cost nearly
three billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
After completing the draft map of human chromosomes, scientists
will turn their work to annotation: learning the function of every
gene and how genes relate to one another. 
</P>
</TEXT>
