<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Becomes International Dunhuang Studies Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DUNHUANG, (GANSU), June 26 (Xinhua) -- An international
symposium on Dunhuang studies will be held next month in Dunhuang
of northwest China's Gansu Province to mark the centennial
anniversary of the discovery of the Sutras Cave and the beginning
of Dunhuang Studies.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman with the Institute of Dunhuang Studies announced
today that a series of activities will be held from July 29
through August 3 in both Beijing and Gansu.
</P>
<P>
In 1900, a Taoist priest, Wang Yuanlu, discovered a cave at the
Mogao Grottoes in Dunhuang which contained more than 50,000 sutras,
documents and paintings of nearly 10 dynasties from the 4th to the
11th century.
</P>
<P>
The Mogao Grottoes was included by the United Nations
Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO) on the
World Heritage List in 1987.
</P>
<P>
Chinese scholars have contributed two-thirds of the 200
academic papers already handed in for the symposium, the largest
event of its kind since the Dunhuang studies was designated a
branch of learning 100 years ago, said Zhang Xiantang, deputy
secretary-general with the Academic Committee of the Institute of
Dunhuang Studies.
</P>
<P>
China has become an international center of Dunhuang studies. "
Chinese scholars have built a complete collection of materials in
fields such as Dunhuang-related literature, grotto archaeology,
and grotto art, and now lead the world with their research on the
subjects," Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
However, the scholars have not had an easy time developing
Dunhuang studies; the majority of Dunhuang documents are scattered
abroad, therefore Chinese researchers in the 1950s and 1960s had
to resort to micro films bought from countries including the
United States, Britain, France and Japan to complete their studies.
</P>
<P>
China has made universally-acknowledged achievements in
Dunhuang studies since 1970s, with the research being expanded
into a dozen fields including religion, economy, nationalities,
languages, astronomy and medicine. Moreover, a number of
encyclopedias on Dunhuang studies by Chinese researchers have been
published.
</P>
<P>
The Institute of Dunhuang Studies, which is based near the
Dunhuang Grottoes, is working with a Hong Kong-based publishing
house on a 30-volume series titled "Collection of Dunhuang
Grottoes." The institute has also published a 22-volume
encyclopedia, "Art of the Dunhuang Grottoes" in cooperation with a
publishing house from east China's Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
Chinese grotto protection organizations, led by the Institute
of Dunhuang Studies, have extended the research of Dunhuang
Studies into the natural sciences. The groups have classified the
grottoes, improved renovation technology used for the murals, and
are using advanced techniques to repair grotto cliff cracks and
prevent deterioration of the caves.
</P>
<P>
Many research centers specialize in Dunhuang studies in China.
Universities and specialized research institutions in Dunhuang,
Beijing, Hangzhou, Wuhan, Lanzhou, and Guangzhou offer advanced
courses in the field. Researchers of Dunhuang studies who are
based in Hong Kong and Taiwan have published lengthy book
collections, including the 140-volume "Dunhuang Treasures."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000626.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Floods Kill Nine in East China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Floods have killed nine people
and affected 365,000 others in east China's Jiangxi Province.
</P>
<P>
The floods have washed away 6,200 houses, devastated eight
counties and more than 7,000 hectares of farmland, resulting in
economic losses of 160 million yuan (about 19.2 million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Heavy rains started to pour in the city of Gangzhou on June 18
and brought about mountain torrents and landslides causing water
levels in rivers to rise.
</P>
<P>
Provincial governor Shu Shengyou has urged officials to take
measures to control floods and safeguard people's lives and
properties.
</P>
<P>
Water in four large reservoirs in the province has risen to an
emergency levels but water in five major rivers in the province is
stable.
</P>
<P>
Officials at the Provincial Flood Control and Drought Relief
Headquarters said they are closely monitoring the floods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
