<DOCNO> XIE20000626.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Honors Major Archaeological Finds of 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- China's State Administration of
Cultural Heritage (SACH) today honored those responsible for the
ten most important archaeological finds of 1999.
</P>
<P>
A number of archaeological teams were awarded certificates, and
the municipal government of Jiangyin in east China's Jiangsu
province and the Quanxing Group Company in southwest China's
Sichuan province received "special contribution" kudos at today's
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The ten winners, selected from a list of more than 400
discoveries in 1999, include the Neolithic ruins near Jiangyin of
Jiangsu Province and the capital of the Yuan Dynasty (1271-1368)
in Zhangbei of Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
China's largest ancient still and the oldest cookbook were
among the top choices.
</P>
<P>
SACH has made its annual selection since 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
