<DOCNO> XIE20000626.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Maintains Communication With Abu Sayyaf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government stressed
Monday that communication lines remain open between government
negotiators and the Abu Sayyaf for the release of 20 hostages in
Sulu province in the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Press Secretary and Presidential Spokesman Ricardo Puno told
reporters here that the government continues to try to expedite
the release of the other hostages.
</P>
<P>
"Discussions are continuing. At least even if no formal
meetings are taking place, the lines of communication have
remained open and the process is continuing for the release of the
balance of the hostages," he said.
</P>
<P>
Puno also disclosed that the government is hopeful that
medical missions for the hostages may be allowed to resume in "
next couple of days."
</P>
<P>
Puno said earlier that the government has ruled out the use of
a"final military option" for the safe release of the 20 hostages
still in the hands of the Abu Sayyaf.
</P>
<P>
Last weekend the Abu Sayyaf released Malaysian hostage
Zulkarniam Bin Hashim, which was termed by chief government
negotiator Robert Aventajado as a sign of goodwill on the part of
the hostage takers.
</P>
<P>
Aventajado stressed that no ransom was paid for Bin Hashim's
release. He said he remains optimistic that the Abu Sayyaf would
continue with the negotiations, which recently went through a
cooling-off period.
</P>
<P>
Hashim took off Monday afternoon for home at the Ninoy Aquino
International Airport in Manila.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Sayyaf group is still holding captive three Germans,
two French, two Finns, two South Africans, one Lebanese, eight
other Malaysians and two Filipinos.
</P>
<P>
The hostages were kidnapped by Abu Sayyaf rebels on April 23
from the diving resort of Sipadan in neighboring Malaysia and
taken to Jolo island in the southern Philippines.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000626.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 41 Die in Philippine Evacuation Centers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Health Secretary Alberto Romualdez said in a statement that 90
percent of the deaths in the evacuation centers were children.
</P>
<P>
Romualdez made the clarification in reaction to published
reports that deaths in evacuations centers in Mindanao have
already reached 92. The same reports tagged the evacuation centers
as "killing fields"themselves.
</P>
<P>
Evacuation centers by definition, Romualdez explained, are
emergency makeshift facilities providing temporary living quarters
for displaced people.
</P>
<P>
"Naturally we can expect overcrowding, poor sanitary conditions
and sometimes even lack of food," he said, even as he assured the
government is addressing the problems.
</P>
<P>
Romualdez said the most common illnesses in the evacuation
centers are infectious in nature including diarrhea, skin
infections and respiratory diseases.
</P>
<P>
"Again we do not deny we have a problem, but there are efforts
to keep the evacuation centers more livable," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Reports said clashes between government troops and Moro Islamic
Liberation Front rebels have forced about 500,000 civilians in
Mindanao flee their homes since April this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000626.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan For International Cooperation in Science </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Speaking at a function, Musharraf said, "We want to belong to
the mainstream of science and development. Therefore, we must
build bridges to the scientific community in the world."
</P>
<P>
He noted that all scientific research must be focused towards
economic development of Pakistan and "it ought to be focused on
the environmental requirement of Pakistan."
</P>
<P>
Referring to Pakistan's nuclear policy, Musharraf said the
rationale behind Islamabad's nuclear policy is purely security and
"we only want to maintain a minimum credible deterrence to deter
any aggression against our homeland."
</P>
<P>
Apart from achieving minimum deterrence capability the main
thrust of Pakistan's nuclear program is on peaceful applications.
</P>
<P>
He said generation of electric power is one of the main tasks
undertaken by the Pakistan Atomic Energy Commission.
</P>
<P>
He said, "I have presided over the meeting of Commission on
Science whose meeting has been held after 11 years and have
committed to allocate 15 billion rupees (283 million U.S. dollars)
for Science and technology."
</P>
<P>
"I very much wish to shape the future of our country with
science and technology. I want to see the development of
technologies like information and biotechnology, which have
immense potential for mankind and can charge the destiny of our
nation," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said, "the future of Pakistan lies in the science and that's
why my government is concentrating in the promotion of scientific
studies and research in the country." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000626.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia to Set Up Export Processing Zones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Zambian government said the planned
 establishment of Export Processing Zones (EPZ) in some parts of
the country is aimed at strengthening Zambia's manufacturing
capacity in the wake of the Common Market for Eastern and Southern
Africa (COMESA) Free Trade Area (FTA).
</P>
<P>
Twelve out of 21 COMESA member states including Zambia have
agreed to reduce their tariffs to zero by October this year under
the FTA.
</P>
<P>
Commerce and Industry Ministry Public Relations Officer, Conrad
 Simuchile, in an interview in Lusaka with reporters on Monday
said, without giving the exact number, that some small towns in
the country had been earmarked for transformation into EPZs.
</P>
<P>
Simuchile explained that manufacturing industries that operate
in EPZs will offer various incentives and rebates on production
costs. This is aimed at attracting and encouraging manufacturing
in the EPZs in particular and the country as a whole, he said.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the promoting manufacturing EPZs will also encourage
 infrastructure development and job creation in the respective
zones.
</P>
<P>
Simuchile said the establishment of the EPZs would follow
cabinet and Parliament approval. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
