<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Hails ACBF's Support in Economic Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's capacity in macro-economic
analysis and development management has substantially improved
through the support of the African Capacity Building Fund (ACBF).
</P>
<P>
Vice President, Christon Tembo, told delegates to the on-going
two-day ACBF "National Focal Point" regional workshop here on
Monday, that Zambia had benefited substantially from the ACBF's
trust fund over the years.
</P>
<P>
The regional workshop attracted delegates from 16 African
countries, various multilateral and bilateral institutions from
within and beyond the African continent.
</P>
<P>
Established in 1991 by 13 African countries, the ACBF was given
a mandate to address capacity needs in the area of micro-economic
policy analysis and development management.
</P>
<P>
Tembo noted that many African countries were faced with similar
problems of foreign debt, HIV/AIDS, economic globalization, civil
strife and aid fatigue which had adversely affected the
development of the continent.
</P>
<P>
"The creation of the ACBF is clear demonstration of the
realization that the problems we face are solvable," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
