<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean, Namibian Troops Urged to Withdraw From Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe and Namibia should
withdraw their troops from the Democratic Republic of the Congo
(DRC) in accordance with the Lusaka ceasefire agreement signed
last July, Ugandan Army Spokesman Phinehas Katirima said Monday.
</P>
<P>
"All warring-parties in the DRC should withdraw their troops.
Zimbabwe and Namibia signed the agreement and they should abide by
it," Katirima told Xinhua in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
"Uganda is doing its part and is withdrawing its troops from
the DRC," he added, referring to the withdrawal of five
battalions back to Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Katirima made the comment on the report that the presidents of
Zimbabwe, the DRC and Namibia agreed at the Sunday's summit in
Harare that the Zimbabwean and Namibian troops will remain in the
Congo.
</P>
<P>
He said all parties concerned should pull out of their troops
from the Congo when U.N. forces are deployed in the DRC. "We hope
the United Nations will deploy its forces at an earlier date," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
