<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Welcomes Publication of Human Gene Map </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The European Union welcomed
Monday the release into the public domain of a working draft of
the complete human genome sequence.
</P>
<P>
"I particularly welcome the release of this sequence into the
public domain and its free accessibility to all researchers," said
EU Research Commissioner Philippe Busquin.
</P>
<P>
He added that a concerted effort is now needed to unleash the
enormous medical, social and economic potential of the human
genome sequence.
</P>
<P>
"Europe will only fully benefit from this new knowledge if a
large public debate on how, why and for which purposes this
discovery is used," said the Belgian, who added that an
international dialogue has to take place on related issues such as
patenting.
</P>
<P>
An international team of scientists have confirmed that they
had completed a working draft of the human genome, all the genes
in the human body.
</P>
<P>
The mapping work was carried out in 16 research centers around
the world. The project has mapped out 97 percent of the human
genome, of which 85 percent has been accurately sequenced.
</P>
<P>
The completion of the mapping of the human genome was hailed as
a scientific milestone that will transform man's knowledge about
himself and will facilitate future developments in the
understanding, treatment and prevention of human diseases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
