<DOCNO> XIE20000626.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Expected to Register Record Trade Surplus in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Russia's trade surplus with non-CIS
(Commonwealth of Independent States) countries in 2000 will hit a
record high of 42.3 billion U.S. dollars, the Russian Economy
Ministry has forecast recently.
</P>
<P>
According to the forecast, Russia's exports outside the CIS in
2000 will amount to 73.8 billion dollars, up 18.3 percent over
last year, while its imports from outside the CIS are expected to
increase 2.6-3.5 percent to 31.5 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Russian trade turnover outside the CIS this year will rise to
105.3 billion dollars, up 13.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
From January to April, Russia's foreign trade turnover surged
30.8 percent from the same period last year to 41.3 billion
dollars, enjoying a surplus of 20.9 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The surplus would reach 26.1 billion dollars if the figures of
the month of May were counted, according to the ministry.
</P>
<P>
In the first five months this year, Russia's trade with CIS
countries soared by 40.5 percent to 11.1 billion dollars from the
same period last year, with the country's exports to CIS countries
jumping 44.4 percent to 6.5 billion dollars and imports by 35.3
percent to 4.6 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
