<HEADLINE> Record Rain Hits Ottawa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ottawa, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Heavy showers caused flooding in
several parts of Canada Sunday, with the capital city of Ottawa
witnessing a record-breaking rainfall, according to Environment
Canada.
</P>
<P>
The pouring lasted 12 hours between 2 a.m. and 2 p.m. to pelt
Ottawa with 46.4 millimeters of rain, breaking the record of 45.6
millimeters last set on the same day in 1988.
</P>
<P>
The month of June is also recorded as the wettest with total
precipitation already reaching 124 millimeters, second only to the
record 174 millimeters in 1943.
</P>
<P>
More than 135 calls came in to the city's emergency line late
Sunday, while in the neighboring Mont-Bleu area, Quebec, about 30
basements were flooded.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere in Quebec, sections of Highway 327 in Lachute were
closed for hours with flooding reported in several municipalities,
including Sainte-Sophie and Saint-Columban.
</P>
<P>
In the western province of Alberta, a savage afternoon storm
pounded Calgary's southwest with golf-ball-sized hailstones and
torrents of rain that flooded one block with more than a meter of
water. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
