<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Executes Drug Dealers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Making a clear and compelling
statement on International Anti-Drug Day today, China executed a
dozen traffickers and publicly burned two tons of confiscated
narcotics.
</P>
<P>
The dealers included three from Taiwan, one Hong Kong resident,
two Shanghai heroin dealers and four drug sellers in northwest
China's Shaanxi Province. Some 226 kg of heroin and 1,376 kg of
methamphetemine, known as "ice," were burned in the open air in
Fujian, east China.
</P>
<P>
In the past two years, Shanghai police have investigated 621
drug cases, nabbed 1,083 suspects and confiscated 48.3 kg of
heroin. Fujian Province in the last five months uncovered 1,370
drug-related cases, involving 795 dealers and 309 kg of drugs.
</P>
<P>
China's modern-day traffickers often use railways to smuggle
drugs, hiding the substances in everything from fruit to tape
recorders and hot pots. Some dealers swallow packets of drugs, or
conceal them in body cavities.
</P>
<P>
From January through May, southwest China's Yunnan Province, a
main drug-dealing base in the country, handled 1,076 drug cases,
sentenced 734 convicted dealers to life in prison or death, and
gave prison terms of up to five years to 525 people.
</P>
<P>
Drug addiction is on the rise among China's young people. And
an increasing number of people from overseas have been involved in
drug-related crimes in the Chinese mainland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
