<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Turkish Coalition Saved, for the Time Being </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- With the fate of a pro-Islamic
partner still undecided and the ties between another two partners
remaining strained, the Turkish coalition government might run into
fresh troubles.
</P>
<P>
The parliamentarians rejected last Thursday a motion to send
former Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz to the supreme court on charges
of fraud, withering a crisis for the coalition government. However,
it is widely believed that the life span of Prime Minister Bulent
Ecevit's three-way cabinet is still a question.
</P>
<P>
The Nationalist Action Party (MHP), Ecevit's far-right coalition
partner, joined the oppositions in calling for a supreme court
trial of Yilmaz, the leader of the coalition's center-right
Motherland Party (ANAP), for graft in land-selling during his term
as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Out of the 394 deputies present in the 550-member parliament,
216 voted against the motion.
</P>
<P>
Under normal conditions, the opposition parties, namely, the
pro-Islamic Virtue Party (FP) and the True Path Party (DYP), would
not hesitate to refer Yilmaz to the supreme court on graft charges.
</P>
<P>
But, the specter that former FP Labor Minister Necati Celik and
DYP leader Tansu Ciller are also facing corruption charges made
them willing to conclude a deal with the ANAP and the Democratic
Left Party (DSP), led by Ecevit who prefers to cabinet stability.
</P>
<P>
Obviously, the deal between the four parties was working without
a hitch. In Thursday's vote, they joined hands, leaving the MHP
alone in its efforts to refer the leaders of the country's two
leading center-right parties, Yilmaz and Ciller, to the supreme
court.
</P>
<P>
The corruption allegations against Yilmaz will prevent the ANAP
leader from having a place in the cabinet. It was believed to be
one of the steps taken by the MHP to compete with ANAP in case of
an early election.
</P>
<P>
The possibility of an early election is real because Turkish
constitutional court will decide whether the pro-Islamic opposition
Virtue Party (FP) is the successor to the defunct Islamic Welfare
Party or not in October.
</P>
<P>
If the court makes a "yes" verdict, the FP will be closed and 70
deputies in the parliament will be dismissed.
</P>
<P>
According to the Constitution, if 5 percent or about 28 of the
550-seat parliament's deputies are absent, the country should be
forced into an early parliamentary election within three months.
</P>
<P>
It was speculated that the MHP and ANAP are trying to damage
each other as a part of their election strategy as the ANAP is
aiming to win the nationalist and conservative votes, wooed also by
the MHP, in the absence of the FP.
</P>
<P>
If the parliament had sent Yilmaz to the supreme court last
week, this would have caused the coalition's collapse. The
coalition has been saved, but for the time being. The ditch between
the two ruling partners will definitely affect the government's
unity.
</P>
<P>
Although the coalition leaders have sent the message that the
government will continue, there is already talk about how long this
may go on.
</P>
<P>
Prior to Thursday's vote, Ecevit said that "it would be
difficult for the government to be exactly as it was in the past.
The quarrel will have its psychological effects."
</P>
<P>
Due to the MHP-ANAP tension, the government will obviously
neither be able to make decisions as rapidly as it did last year,
nor work harmoniously because their ministers may refuse to
undersign decrees sponsored by each other, causing a deadlock.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
