<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Eases Ban on Local Weekly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Kumaratunga has issued the directive to the Competent
Authority that ban on The Sunder Leader "be lifted with effective
from July 31, 2000 after a period of two months and 10 days," said
a government statement.
</P>
<P>
The president made the decision after considering the
recommendation of the Advisory Committee, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The Competent Authority Ariya Rubesinghe on May 22 banned The
Sunday Leader and other publications of the M/s Leader
Publications (Pvt.) Ltd. for six months after several warnings to
obey the censorship laws.
</P>
<P>
The proprietor of the publications had made an appeal to the
Advisory Committee appointed by the president under the Emergency
Regulation seeking the revocation of the prohibition order. The
Advisory Committee thus had recommended to the president that the
six months ban be reduced to three months.
</P>
<P>
On May 4, Sri Lanka slapped censorship on both the local and
foreign media as fighting escalated in the northern Jaffna
peninsula between government troops and Tamil Tiger rebels who are
engaged in a ferocious assault in a bid to retake their former
stronghold of Jaffna.
</P>
<P>
The government lifted the censorship on the foreign media on
June 5 as government troops had managed to stall the rebel assault.
</P>
<P>
Government officials had said the censorship on the local media
will definitely be lifted before the general elections which must
be held by mid-November. 
</P>
</TEXT>
