<HEADLINE> EU Cautious on Zimbabwean Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)
cautiously welcomed Monday the high turnout in the Zimbabwean
parliamentary elections which it said was registered in a "very
difficult" situation.
</P>
<P>
"The union welcomed the very high turnout despite incidents of
intimidation at polling stations and the union is waiting for the
final result," said Gunnar Wiegand, spokesman for European Union
External Relations Commissioner Christophe Patten.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation bloc will keep on building a strong partnership
with a democratic Zimbabwe, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
This was the first official reaction by the union toward the
Zimbabwean elections which were held on Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The EU has dispatched 109 observers to monitor the elections
held after four months of holding white-owned farms by veterans
from the liberation war that led to the Zimbabwean independence
from Rhodesia in 1980.
</P>
<P>
A total of 5 million people were eligible for casting their
ballots in the elections for the 120 parliamentary seats and the
turnout was reported to appear the highest since 1980.
</P>
<P>
The EU has provided the southern African country with 1.83
million euro (1.75 million U.S. dollars) for the preparation and
process of the two-day elections.
</P>
<P>
Vote counting began on Monday and the final result is expected
to be out on July 3. 
</P>
</TEXT>
