<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Calls for New Regulations for Globalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 26 (Xinhua) -- France Monday called for the
adoption of new regulations by the international community and
individual states to cope with globalization and the problems it
is bringing about.
</P>
<P>
The French State Secretary for Exterior Trade, Francois Huwart,
said that while globalization is an opportunity for all countries,
individual states should reach an agreement among them on how to
take advantage of it, discuss its prior objectives and attain a
consensus on the methods to cope with its problems.
</P>
<P>
He made the statement at a forum of the Organization for
Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), which was focused on
the perspective of launching a new round of negotiations on trade
liberalization after the failure of the World Trade Organization (
WTO) talks in Seattle last November.
</P>
<P>
Official representatives from OECD's 29 member countries opened
the forum on Monday at the OECD headquarters in northwest Paris.
</P>
<P>
Huwart said that in the face of globalization, a balanced
economic development for all countries, jobs, education, health
and environment are the vital issues that all countries are
concerned with.
</P>
<P>
All these questions also call for the definition of new
national and international norms either through voluntary consent
or through constraint of international conventions, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that many new questions, such as bio-technology, cannot
be treated within the national or regional frameworks only but
should be approached with international cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Huwart said that some international organizations are faced
with a "crisis of legitimacy," which obliges them to carry out
reforms and to be endowed with more efficiency, transparency and
democracy.
</P>
<P>
He was apparently referring to the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) and the WTO, which were the targets of many protesters
during the WTO talks in Seattle last November and World Bank and
IMF yearly conference in Washington two months ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
