<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, June 26 (Xinhua) -- South Korean Foreign Affairs and
Trade Minister Lee Young Binn will pay an official visit to Moscow
on June 28-29 to prepare for Russian President Vladimir Putin's
visit to Seoul, said the Russian Foreign Ministry Monday.
</P>
<P>
During Lee's stay in Moscow, "the parties will exchange their
opinions on a number of questions, with a special emphasis on the
Russian president's upcoming visit to the Republic of Korea and
the situation on the Korean Peninsula after the recent first inter-
Korean summit," Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Alexander Losyukov
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Losyukov said the two sides will also discuss a number of
other international issues.
</P>
<P>
The very fact of the South Korean minister's visit to Russia "
indicates the active role of Russia" in the regulation of the
situation on the Korean Peninsula, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Whether Russia will play a more active role will depend on the
development of the situation in this region, the deputy minister
said.
</P>
<P>
Last week, South Korean deputy Minister of Foreign Affairs and
Trade Ban Ki Moon visited Moscow to inform Russia about the
results of the historic summit between the Democracy People's
Republic of Korean (DPRK) leader Kim Jong Il and South Korean
President Kim Dae Jung.
</P>
<P>
During the meetings with Ban, the Russian side expressed its
readiness to participate in meetings of various formats aimed at
solving the Korean problem and to create a favorable atmosphere
for the dialogue between the DPRK and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Last Tuesday, Putin confirmed his intention to visit the
Republic of Korea in the near future after a planned trip to the
DPRK.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the Kremlin announced that Putin had
decided to pay a working visit to the DPRK on July 19 prior to the
Group-8 summit slated for late July in Japan's Okinawa. 
</P>
