<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ten Drug-Related Criminals Executed in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- To mark the International Anti-
Drug Day, the Supreme People's Court of China announced today that
ten drug-related criminals were executed and another fifteen were
sentenced to life or fixed-term imprisonment in three separate
cases.
</P>
<P>
The first case involves Chen Xinyuan, from Taiwan, Cai Dehui, a
Hong Kong businessman and Gu Jianzhu, a farmer in Fujian Province,
who trafficked 115,000 grams of heroin from the Chinese mainland
to Taiwan in 1992 and 1993. The three were all sentenced to death
by local courts in 1998. Another six accomplices were sentenced to
fix-term imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
In another case, three farmers in southwest China's Yunnan
Province--Zhang Jinfu, Zhou Weijun and Yang Shaogui--were also
executed today for smuggling 76,000 grams of heroin.
</P>
<P>
The execution of another four was made in south China's
Guangdong Province. Lin Weijun, Yang Huicheng and Lin Junqiang
from Huizhou in Guangdong and Lu Hui from Sichuan Province were
sentenced to death for making 1,500 kilograms of methamphetamine,
known as "ice," and 1,500 kilograms of methamphetamine liquid.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme People's Court recently approved all above verdicts
and authorized the execution of the ten criminals.
</P>
<P>
All ten criminals were deprived of their political rights and
personal belonging, according to the Supreme People's Court
announcement.
</P>
</TEXT>
