<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore's Industrial Output Grows by 10.9 Pct in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's industrial output
increased by 10.9 percent year-on-year in May 2000 with cumulative
output for the first five months this year expanding by 13.9
percent compared to the same period in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The expansion was mainly supported by the 20.5 percent growth
year-on-year in the electronics cluster which saw rise in
production of semiconductor industry, the computer peripheral and
the telecommunication equipment segments and a fall in that of
data storage segment and computer industry.
</P>
<P>
Chemical cluster led the growth in May 2000, increasing by 33.
4 percent over a year ago with pharmaceuticals and industrial/
speciality chemical segments surging up heftily by 113 percent and
29.8 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
However, the production of petroleum products remained in the
doldrums with a decline of 17.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Output of engineering cluster went up 13.5 percent in May 2000
compared to the same period last year and the increase was mainly
contributed by the precision and process engineering segments as
the transport engineering segment contracted by 5 percent in May
2000.
</P>
<P>
Compared to the same period in 1999, output of the electronics,
chemical and engineering clusters registered a cumulative growth
of 21.3 percent, 9.7 percent and 8.7 percent respectively in the
period from January to May this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
