<DOCNO> XIE20000626.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Discusses Strategy to Develop Small Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- A Workshop to discuss an Asian
Development Bank (ADB) strategy for the development of small and
medium scale enterprises (SMEs) in some areas of the Philippines
and Indonesia opened Monday in Manila.
</P>
<P>
The ADB said in a press release that the three-day workshop
aims at developing a strategy to address the constraints that
hinder the development of the SMEs in Philippines' Mindanao and
Palawan and Indonesia's Kalimantan and Sulawesi.
</P>
<P>
According to the ADB, the new strategy proposes to provide the
SMEs access to technologies, markets and credits, and to support
coordination of the ongoing and planned development activities.
</P>
<P>
The ADB said supporting the private sector is an effective way
of spurring development and combating poverty in these relatively
underdeveloped areas.
</P>
<P>
The bank estimates that SME development will cost 80 million U.
S.dollars each for Indonesia and the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
To maximize the impact of its SME effort, the ADB is seeking
the support of governments, the private sector, the international
donor community and nongovernmental organizations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
