<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's War Veterans Leader to Refuse Poll Result If Ruling Party Loses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's war veterans leader
Chenjerai Hunzvi Monday warned that the war veterans will go back
to the bush if the ruling Zimbabwe African National
Union-Patriotic Front (Zanu-pf) loses the parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
He told the Zimbabwe News Agency that they would take that move
to prevent the country from sliding back into the hands of
reactionaries.
</P>
<P>
"This is idle talk," said leader of the opposition Movement for
 Democratic Change Morgan Tsvangirai, adding, "No sensible
Zimbabwean will accept that. Why did they participate in the
election if they did not want any other result?"
</P>
<P>
Zanu-pf Secretary for Administration Didymus Mutasa said, "It
is a bit too early for anything. We will cross the bridge when we
get there. Zanu- pf is confident of winning most seats in the
country."
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe held its fifth parliamentary election over the
weekend, which for the first time was tightly contested in all the
constituencies by other opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's war veterans have occupied over 1,500 white farms
since February this year to pressure the government to speed up
the land reform process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
