<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Development Bank Holds Forum in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
is holding a mayor forum in Shanghai focusing on "fighting against
urban poverty".
</P>
<P>
Mayors of about sixty cities and deputies from non-government
organizations in the Asia-Pacific region take part in the four-day
event. The sixty cities in the Asia-Pacific region now has a
population of 200 million. About one-fourth of them live in
poverty.
</P>
<P>
According ADB statistics, the Asia-Pacific region has about one
billion poor people. In the coming ten years, the cities in
developing countries will face problems of urban poverty as
economic development bring unemployment and polluted environment.
Participants at the forum will exchange ideas on tackling the
problem.
</P>
<P>
Chen Liangyu, vice mayor of Shanghai, said that Shanghai would
like to share its experience with developing cities in the Asia-
Pacific region. He said that Shanghai, China's largest commercial
center, will increase jobs by about 300,000 in three years and
further improve the social welfare system.
</P>
<P>
Participants come from 17 countries including Bangladesh,
Bhutan, Cambodia, the United States, Indonesia, Pakistan, Sri
Lanka, Vietnam and China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
