<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Stocks Close Higher, But in Thin Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong stocks closed higher
Monday, boosted by the gains of blue chips, but the trade volume
recorded the lowest this year.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Hang Seng Index rose 240.83 points, or 1.53
percent, to close at 15,978.91, with the turnover of only 6.251
billion HK dollars (about 801 million U.S. dollars), compared to
the 8.425 billion HK dollars (1.08 billion U.S.dollars) last
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Major blue chips, like China Telecom, led the market increase,
said brokers, but many investors stood on the sideline, waiting
for the U.S. interest-rate setting meeting later this week.
</P>
<P>
Sub-indices of Finance, Utilities, Properties, Commerce and
Industry all gained by 1.05 percent, 0.64 percent, 0.80 percent
and 2.03 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
China-related stocks ended mixed with the Hang Seng China
Enterprises Index up 2.00 percent, but the Hang Seng China-
Affiliated Corp Index down 0.74 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng IT Index rose 2.23 percent, while the Hang Seng
IT Portfolio Index lost 0.06 percent.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong stocks fell 11.96 points, or 0.08 percent, to open at
15,726.12 Monday. The stock prices then rebounded and registered
133.80 points up, or 0.85 percent, to close the morning session at
15,871.88. 
</P>
</TEXT>
