<HEADLINE> Malaysia Supports Philippine Efforts for Hostage Release </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia Monday said it will
continue to support the Philippine Government's efforts to secure
the release of the hostages being held by an armed group in the
Southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Foreign Minister Syed Hamid Albar made the statement
here after talks with Alexander Aguirre, national security adviser
to Philippine President Joseph Estrada.
</P>
<P>
Syed Hamid told reporters that a third team of Malaysian
medical volunteers would leave for the Philippines soon to treat
the hostages.
</P>
<P>
The hostage issue could not be prolonged as there are among the
hostages people whose health has been disrupted, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said Aguirre conveyed a message of thanks from the
Philippine government to Malaysia for its support and cooperation
in efforts to secure the release of the hostages.
</P>
<P>
He said that Aguirre had also reiterated that his government
would continue negotiating with the Moro Islamic Liberation Front
(MILF) to find a peaceful solution to the ongoing problems in the
Southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
"Aguirre also expressed the vital importance for strong and
close relations between the Philippines and Malaysia," Syed Hamid
said.
</P>
<P>
Expressing dismay over reports by sections of the Philippine
media, which he termed as inaccurate, Syed Hamid said "we regret
baseless and untrue statements."
</P>
<P>
Malaysia is satisfied that the Philippine government has
disassociated itself from such statements, he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said Malaysia and the Philippines are aware about
the coming here of MILF members to meet OIC leaders and members
who are in Kuala Lumpur for the 27th Islamic Conference of Foreign
Ministers which begins here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said "there is an agreement among all ASEAN countries that
their citizens can come without a visa. They are Philippine
passport holders and are welcome unless they are criminals."
</P>
<P>
On whether the MILF has applied for observer status, Syed Hamid
said," nothing in the agenda. So I cannot discuss something not in
the agenda."
</P>
<P>
He said that during the OIC meeting here, the Philippines would
submit a report on the implementation of the MNLF peace settlement
in the Southern Philippines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
