<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Takes Measures to Ensure Food Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam has decided to strictly
maintain its present rice acreage, about four million hectares,
for at least 10 years, to ensure the rice output of the country.
</P>
<P>
The decision, according to a report of local English daily
Vietnam News on Monday, is part of a Vietnamese government
resolution signed by Prime Minister Phan Van Khai last week on
measures to restructure the rural economy and promote farm product
marketing.
</P>
<P>
The resolution of the Vietnamese government says that of the
proposed 33 million tonnes of unhusked rice, 25 million tonnes
will be earmarked for domestic consumption and the country's food
reserve, and the remaining eight million tonnes for export.
</P>
<P>
According to the decision, the existing irrigation and drainage
network of the country must be ensured for four million hectares
of rice fields.
</P>
<P>
The resolution also stipulates that other food crops will be
cultivated on land unsuitable for rice, like swampy and coastal
areas.
</P>
<P>
Vegetables and fruit trees will be grown on arable areas
adjacent to major urban centers.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam has reaped bumper harvests of rice for many years
running. The country exported more than 4.5 million tonnes of rice
in 1999, becoming the second biggest rice exporter in the World.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
