<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Plans to Make 25 Pct of Villages Drug-free </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June (Xinhua) -- Thai government plans to make 25
percent of villages nationwide drug-free by next year, a senior
anti-drug official said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The plan is to fight the spread of drugs at village level and
target 17,000 of the country's 70,000 villages, or about 25
percent," Rasamee Wisthawe, deputy chief of the Office of the
Narcotics Control Board (ONCB), was quoted by Thai News Agency as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on Monday's UN-designated International Anti-narcotics
Day, he said the drug problem had spread to the grassroots level
and that even school children were now being targeted by drug
trafficking.
</P>
<P>
Currently, only 6,700 villages nationwide are free of illegal
drugs, according to him.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, an joint rehabilitation project for drug addicts is
being conducted by the Public Health and Labor ministries, the
Correction Department and the military, the Thai News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The first batch of 40 drug addicts will on July 5 be sent to
military camps to learn military discipline and undergo
rehabilitation treatment, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
