<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Oil Minister Resigns over Refinery Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti Oil Minister Sheikh
Saud Nasser Al-Sabah Monday announced he has tendered his
resignation to the emir over a refinery blast that killed four
workers Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Saud told parliament at its weekly session that although
he is not criminally accountable for the incident, his political
responsibilities have obliged him to resign.
</P>
<P>
It is not immediately known whether Emir Sheikh Jaber Al-Ahmed
Al-Sabah has accepted the resignation.
</P>
<P>
The minister added the main officials in the oil sector,
including those overseeing the state-owned Kuwait National
Petroleum Co. that owns and runs the country's three oil
refineries, also have submitted their resignations.
</P>
<P>
And a technical committee has been formed to investigate the
cause of the accident.
</P>
<P>
Four oil workers were killed and almost 50 others injured in
Sunday's blast, caused by a leak in a gas pipeline at the Mina al-
Ahmedi refinery, located about 40 kilometers south of capital
Kuwait City.
</P>
<P>
Mina al-Ahmedi refinery, Kuwait's biggest oil refinery, employs
1,450 people and has a capacity of 444,000 barrels per day.
</P>
</TEXT>
