<HEADLINE> Civil Emergency State Imposed in Maluku, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Chief of the Indonesian National
Police (Polri) Gen. Rusdihardjo said here Monday that the state of
civil emergency have been imposed in the country's Maluku province
as of Sunday (June 25).
</P>
<P>
"The civilian emergency status has been in force since Sunday
and we hope that it will be effective in overcoming the situation
there. This move will be more effective to overcome situation
there," Rusdihardjo was quoted by Suara Pembaruan daily as saying.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the new status empowered the military to
isolate the province and conduct raids and checks.
</P>
<P>
"In line with the imposition of state of civil emergency,
curfew also has been imposed in the province although there have
not yet been an official announcement," he added.
</P>
<P>
He also said that due to the limitation of police personnel in
the province, "the Indonesian Military (TNI) will take and decide
any necessary measures such as weapons raid and isolation," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Maluku province and the neighboring province of North Maluku
has witnessed communal bloodshed involving Moslems and Christians
for more than one year.
</P>
<P>
More than two Thousands people have been killed during the
bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
President Abdurrahman Wahid said on Friday that the government
has banned outsiders from entering Maluku province. 
</P>
