<HEADLINE> Vietnam Develops Tea Industry and Boosts Tea Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam has steadily developed its
tea industry and boosted tea export in past 10 years, raising its
share in the world tea market from 1.7 percent in 1995 to 4
percent in 1999, Vietnam's official news agency VNA reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The country now has about 82,000 hectares (ha) of tea,
including 4,900 ha of new plantings, with an average per-ha yield
of 4.32 tonnes of tea buds and an annual output of more than 60,
000 tonnes.
</P>
<P>
The country's 102 tea exporters have increased export turnover
to 50 million U.S. dollars a year. In the first six months of this
year, Vietnam earned 21 million U.S. dollars from tea export, a
year-on-year increase of 32.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese tea industry is making efforts to attain the
targets of an annual output of 70,000 tonnes by 2005 and 80
percent of the output for export. 
</P>
</TEXT>
