<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OECD Threatens to Impose Sanctions on Tax Havens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development (OECD) Monday threatened to impose
sanctions against 35 tax havens, some of them closely linked with
France, Britain and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The OECD accused these tax havens of practicing a "prejudicial
tax competition" by seeking to attract banking deposits from
individuals and companies who want to avoid paying taxes in their
own countries.
</P>
<P>
The tax havens on the OECD list include the British Virgin
Islands, Cook Islands, Marshall Islands, the U.S. Virgin Islands
and Vanuatu.
</P>
<P>
The OECD said that the warning is aimed at making sure that the
duty of tax-paying must be done equally everywhere in the world
and that tax must not be a key factor in investment decision-
making.
</P>
<P>
The 35 tax havens will have to decide in the next 12 months
whether to cooperate with the OECD or not to "eliminate the
prejudicial characters of their (tax) regime from now until the
end of 2005," said the OECD.
</P>
<P>
It said that the 29-member countries of the organization will
adopt "a common approach" including "defensive measures against
the territories which refuse to cooperate."
</P>
<P>
So far, only France has called for sanctions against the tax
havens which refuse to cooperate in the fight against financial
crimes such as money laundering.
</P>
<P>
Last Thursday, an OECD-affiliated organization accused 15
countries and territories of refusing to cooperate in the fight
against financial crimes.
</P>
<P>
These countries include Israel, Russia, the Philippines and
Lebanon, according to a statement published by the Group of
Financial Action on Capital Laundering. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000626.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Czech First Quarter GDP Grows 4.4 percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Czech Republic's gross domestic
product GDP) rose by 4.4 percent year-on-year in the first quarter
of 2000, the Czech Statistical Bureau (CSU) announced on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The bureau said that in current prices the GDP amounted to 439
billion korun (11.5 billion U.S. dollars) in the period. After an
experimental seasonal adjustment, the GDP was up by 1.3 percent
from the fourth quarter of 1999, it added.
</P>
<P>
The figure was much better than expected. The market had
expected a 2.5-percent GDP growth. Economists said they would
revise their full year forecasts.
</P>
<P>
The Czech koruna jumped after the figure was released to 35.89
to the euro, from 35.99 before the data.
</P>
<P>
Analysts attributed the result mainly to booming exports, which
were up 29.5 percent year-on-year. It is tied mainly to
developments in Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
