<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. General Assembly Holds Special Session on Social Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations General Assembly
(UNGA) began a week-long special session here Monday to address
social development issues amidst the heightened concern over such
social issues as poverty, employment and worker rights in the age
of globalization.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, Danish Prime Minister Poul
Nyrup Rasmussen, Swiss President Adolf Ogi, and Chinese Vice
Premier Wen Jiabao were among more than 100 heads of state and
heads of delegations and observers present at the opening session.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the special session is to advance the global social
development agenda that was set at the 1995 World Summit for
Social Development (Social Summit) in Copenhagen, Denmark,
according to a U.N. press release.
</P>
<P>
After reviewing the progress and the obstacles encountered in
implementing the outcome of the Social Summit, countries
participating in the special session are expected to suggest and
agree upon new initiatives that will enhance efforts to create
jobs, reduce poverty and address a wide array of other social
concerns.
</P>
<P>
On Monday afternoon, Annan will launch a landmark report on
poverty reduction entitled "Better World for All." The report is
an unprecedented collaborative effort by the U.N., the World Bank,
the International Monetary Fund, and the Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development.
</P>
<P>
The joint report finds that by 2015 world poverty can be
significantly decreased if developing and industrialized countries
implement their commitments to attack the root causes of poverty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
