<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rich Countries Should Play Due Role in Poverty Reduction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Secretary-General
Kofi Annan said here Monday that the rich countries have an
indispensable role to play in reducing global poverty.
</P>
<P>
"It is only natural that the poor countries of the world, which
have so few resources of their own, should look for help to the
rich ones," Annan told the opening meeting of the 24th special
session of the U.N. General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
He urged the rich countries to further open their markets, to
provide deeper and faster debt relief, and to give more and better
focused development aid.
</P>
<P>
"Many of those rich countries have acute social problems of
their own," Annan said. "But none of them can be indifferent to
the social conditions in which so many people in poor countries
live."
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the U.N. chief said that the leaders and
peoples of developing countries should also "show real
determination to mobilize their own resources, above all their own
human resources, to deal with their own social problems."
</P>
<P>
Otherwise, he cautioned, those changes are less likely to come,
and will bring few real benefits even if they do come.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the relationship between economic growth and
social development, Annan pointed out that social and economic
welfare are not separate concepts.
</P>
<P>
"Without economic prosperity, no country can provide for all
the social needs of its citizens. But nor can any country be
called truly prosperous so long as many of its citizens are left
to fend for themselves against ignorance, hardship and disease,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"Nor yet can any country achieve prosperity by subordinating
all social concerns to the achievement of a few quantitative
benchmarks," he said. "What matters in the last resort is the
quality of life, a big part of which is the feeling that you
belong freely to your society, and that it also belongs to you."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000626.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strike by Air France Controllers Gravely Disrupts Flights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 26 (Xinhua) -- A 24-hour strike by controllers of
Air France on Monday is disrupting most of the internal flights of
France and many medium-haul flights between France and European
countries.
</P>
<P>
Air France officials estimate that 90 percent of the air
traffic across the French sky is expected to be disrupted on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The air company will guarantee only 15 percent of the internal
flights and medium-haul flights to other European countries on
Monday, while 60 percent of the long-haul flights to overseas
destinations will be secured.
</P>
<P>
The French private air company AOM has canceled all its flights
from Paris to Pergignan in southwest France, Toulon and Zurich,
and the flights by all air companies from Paris to Nice and
Marseille are seriously disrupted.
</P>
<P>
British Airways has canceled or delayed 50 percent of its
flights to France, while the Dutch KLM, has canceled all flights
to France and the German Lufthansa can fly only one plane out of
seven to France.
</P>
<P>
To alleviate the pressure on passengers, the French state
railway company SNCF is providing 5,000 extra seats in trains
linking Paris and the northern city of Lille with southern French
cities and the Swiss city of Geneva.
</P>
<P>
The air controllers are protesting a European plan called "
Unique European Sky," which is aimed at rationalizing all air
traffic across Europe to solve the serious problem of delays in
departure and arrival by planes.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, more than 30 percent of the planes flying among
European states delayed in their departure by an average 15
minutes, resulting in billions of euros of loss.
</P>
<P>
The European plan could result in more privatization of air
companies, said the air controllers who oppose privatization of
their jobs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000626.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oman Likely to Enter WTO in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Oman is likely to become a member
of the World Trade Organization (WTO) by November this year, Said
Al-Riyami, an economic expert of Oman's Ministry of Commerce and
Industries has predicted.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Dubai-based daily "Gulf News" printed
on Monday, the expert said the working party's report and protocol
on Oman's accession are expected to be adopted on July 6 in Geneva,
adding it is now only a formality for Oman to get its WTO's
membership.
</P>
<P>
Al-Riyami, who will be part of Oman's delegation to Geneva,
said all outstanding issues have been resolved concerning Oman's
entry into the WTO.
</P>
<P>
Legislations relating to trade-related intellectual property
rights (Trips), customs valuation, technical barrier to trade
(TBT), sanitary and phyto-sanitary measures and import licensing
procedures have either been promulgated or are to be enacted soon,
he added.
</P>
<P>
"This will be our fifth formal working party meeting in Geneva,
having held eight rounds of bilateral negotiations with Japan, the
U.S., the European Union, Canada, New Zealand, Australia, India,
Switzerland, Mexico and Kirghiz Republic," said the expert.
</P>
<P>
Oman applied for WTO membership in 1996, and has been working
diligently to join the trade body since then.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
