<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Oman is discussing with international investors on
setting up a joint venture to build a 250-million-U.S.-dollar
polypropylene plant in the northern city of Sohar, a project
official said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"Various international companies have shown interest in the
polypropylene project," Mohammed bin Suleiman Al-Kindy, Sohar
refinery project business manager was quoted by Monday's Dubai-
based Gulf News daily as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said it was too early to name the parties.
</P>
<P>
Oman said in May it was conducting a study to build the
polypropylene plant next to a planned 75,000-barrel-per-day
refinery in Sohar.
</P>
<P>
Officials earlier said that the refinery would provide the raw
materials for the new plant, which would process 300,000 tons of
propylene annually to produce polypropylene.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Following promising discoveries in the Azerbaijani
Shahdeniz natural gas project, Turkey has expressed willingness to
buy Azeri natural gas, reported Turkish Daily News on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Energy officials say Azeri natural gas is economically reliable
because only a 280-kilometer-long natural gas pipeline needs to be
built. A 490-kilometer pipeline from Azeri capital of Baku to the
Georgia-Azerbaijan border already exists.
</P>
<P>
Ankara is expected to make a written commitment in July in order
to start work on the pipeline as soon as possible and to ensure the
supply of natural gas by the winter of 2002.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Oman Sunday signed a three-year contract with
Japan's Petroleum Energy Center (PEC) to improve the safety and
reliability of its 85,000-barrel-per-day refinery, a senior
official said.
</P>
<P>
"We have signed a three-year deal with PEC to optimize the
safety aspects and reliability of the refinery," Takaya Sugimura,
the refinery's general manager of maintenance, was quoted by
Monday's Dubai-based Gulf News daily as saying.
</P>
<P>
He did not disclose the value of the deal.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The World Bank plans to contribute some 500 million U.
S. dollars to a proposed fund aimed at encouraging Turkey's use of
renewable energy resources, reported Turkish Daily News on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The bank urges the Turkish government to give priority to the
use of renewable energy resources, such as hydro, wind and solar
power, which provide solid and long-term solutions through a
country's own resources.
</P>
<P>
Government officials are presently working on incentives to make
the sector appealing.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Abu Dhabi Duty Free (ADDF) will launch the world's
first duty free credit card next month, reported Monday's Dubai-
based Khaleej Times daily.
</P>
<P>
The card, to be launched on July 15, will be issued in two
categories, Classic and Gold, to cater to different income groups,
said an ADDF spokesman.
</P>
<P>
ADDF recently signed an agreement with the National Bank of Abu
Dhabi (NBAD)to complete formalities for the card.
</P>
<P>
The card will be provided in association with NBAD and Visa
International. 
</P>
</TEXT>
