<HEADLINE> Merchant Ship Attacked by Rebels in Northern Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 26 (Xinhua) -- A Sri Lankan merchant ship was
attacked and badly damaged by separatist Tamil Tiger rebels early
on Monday off the northern waters, a government statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the MV Mercs Uhana had been attacked around
2:30 a.m. Monday by suicide cadres of the Liberation Tigers of
Tamil Eelam (LTTE) at sea off Point Pedro in Sri Lanka's northern
coast.
</P>
<P>
It said, "21 out of 28 crew members have been rescued and the
fire on board the ship has been brought under control."
</P>
<P>
The fate of seven other crew members is not immediately known.
</P>
<P>
The ship had been chartered by private traders to transport
food and other essential items to Jaffna where government troops
fought pitched battles with the LTTE rebels until last month and
stalled a rebel onslaught to recapture its former stronghold of
Jaffna.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels have been fighting for a separate homeland for
minority Tamils in Sri Lanka's north and east since 1983.
</P>
<P>
Military officials said efforts were being made to tow the
damaged ship to safe waters. They said the LTTE rebels might
mistake the ship for one carrying weapons to government forces in
Jaffna. 
</P>
