<HEADLINE> Indonesia Refuses External Military Aid to Stop Communal  Bloodshed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government will not
ask for military aid from external forces to overcome the ongoing
communal bloodshed in Maluku and North Maluku provinces, a senior
official said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Minister of Foreign Affairs Alwi Shihab
said, "we are still able to handle the ongoing communal bloodshed
in Maluku. We will not ask for military help from foreign
countries. I don't think so. I don't agree on that point. But if
they (foreign countries) will give infrastructure or humanitarian
relief, we will receive that. But not military."
</P>
<P>
"It is clear that the government will do its best to stop
bloodshed in Maluku and North Maluku provinces," Shihab stressed,
adding that foreign countries including the United States have
given positive response over the government's policy in handling
sectarian conflicts in the country.
</P>
<P>
"And the United States government has given their support to
Indonesia in handling communal conflicts in Ambon," he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, after deciding to close Maluku province from the
outsiders on Friday, the government now has been considering to
impose state of civil emergency in Maluku and North Maluku
provinces in a bid to calm down situation and stop violence there
which has claimed thousands of lives.
</P>
<P>
Reports said at least 206 people have been killed in the fresh
clashes between Muslims and Christians which started on June 19 in
North Maluku province and Ambon, capital of Maluku province.
</P>
<P>
Separately, Minister of Law and Legal Affairs Yusril Ihza
Mahendra said, "state of civil emergency is deserved to be imposed
in Poso (a city in the country's Central Sulawesi province),
Maluku province, and North Maluku province."
</P>
<P>
"We can't let communal bloodshed continues to happen there. We
have to do something, now," Mahendra stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
