<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Review Laws on Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian government
said it will review all existing laws and regulations that
restricted the flow of investment into the country.
</P>
<P>
The official Daily News Monday quoted the Minister for Justice
and Constitutional Affairs Bakari Mwapachu as saying that if
there are any laws hampering the process of doing business in the
country, the government will amend such legislations or enact new
ones.
</P>
<P>
The minister reiterated the government's commitment to create a
business- friendly atmosphere for investors and traders, saying
his ministry is ready to amend laws and change outdated policies
to go in line with today's business trends.
</P>
<P>
According to a study recently conducted by the Confederation of
Tanzania Industries (CTI), quite a number of legislations are
making it difficult for entrepreneurs to do business.
</P>
<P>
Legislations said to be scaring away investors include the
Employment Ordinance Act, which allegedly prohibits the business
of recruitment.
</P>
<P>
The Emergency Powers Act and provisions in tax laws such as the
Value Added Tax Act are also described by investors as
restrictive. 
</P>
