<HEADLINE> Kenyan Students Urged to Avoid Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Vice-President George
Saitoti has urged students in the country to shun acts of
hooliganism and maintain peace, the Daily Nation newspaper
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Saitoti, who on Sunday spoke at the official opening of a
Matssia police post in Kajiado District in southern Kenya, said
students should avoid resorting to violence whenever a problem
arise, but instead, seek dialog with the administration in the
learning institutions.
</P>
<P>
Recently, students in a number of high learning institutions
went into violence and damaged public properties in protest to a
nationwide power rationing.
</P>
<P>
The vice-president cautioned students that they would have
themselves to blame if they did not make good use of their time in
school.
</P>
<P>
Saitoti also urged parents and teachers associations, school
board of governors and university councils to pay maximum
attention to the running of their institutions.
</P>
<P>
The government will punish criminals taking advantage of power
rationing to cause mayhem during the night, Saitoti said,
attributing the rise in crime to the proliferation of firearms
into Kenya from neighboring states. 
</P>
