<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Leads Drug Users to New, Healthy Life (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Forty-three year old Wen Zengjun
would have taken it as a dream: a drug addict as he was in the
past, he has became a boss again.
</P>
<P>
"The police has given me a second life," Wen recalled. He was
found in a coma in the street because of drug overdose during one
winter night two years ago. The patrol police rushed him to
hospital immediately.
</P>
<P>
Wen was sent by the local government to a mandatory drug
rehabilitation center after he left hospital in 1998. Five years
of drug addiction made Wen penniless.
</P>
<P>
The only mandatory drug rehabilitation center in Hohhot is
located in the heart of the city with no armed police.
</P>
<P>
After being let out from center, he started a restaurant in
Hohhot, capital city of north China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous
Region.
</P>
<P>
Liu Xiaoya, his wife, said that Wen lost 300,000 yuan (about 36,
145 U.S. dollars) the family had obtained by managing a butcher
shop. Besides, Wen had borrowed money to buy drug without his wife
's knowing.
</P>
<P>
"I asked for a divorce many times," said Liu.
</P>
<P>
"But I was told by police and social workers that only love
could help my husband resolve the problem."
</P>
<P>
Their 18-year old son knew nothing about his father's addiction.
He goes about his studies like any other students. His father's
addiction is kept private by the center.
</P>
<P>
Drug abuse has become an increasingly serious problem in China
in recent years. By the end of 1999, there were 680,000 drug users
in China, up by 14.3 per cent or 85,000 addicts compared to the
figure in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Almost three fourths of China's reported 17,000 HIV carriers in
1999 who were drug addicts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000626.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Leads Drug Users to New, Healthy Life (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Wen had debts problems after he was released from the
Rehabilitation Center.
</P>
<P>
The local government offered Wen a helping hand by providing
him with a low-rent shop and tax exemption. Wen's restaurant
brought him a daily turnover of over 200 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Drug addicts like Wen always get help from the government after
they were off the habit, said Bao Hongli, an official with the
Hohhot drug control office. The government helps them find work
and provides a pension for those who cannot work.
</P>
<P>
"We must take care of them just like a mother would take care
of her children," said Li Guizhen, a 60-year-old woman in charge
of the Guanghua No. 1 Neighborhood Committee in Hohhot who was
helping a former drug user find work.
</P>
<P>
There are currently about 200 people in the center receiving
treatment, 70 percent of whom are self-funded. The rest is covered
by the government.
</P>
<P>
People here get up at seven and do morning exercises before
learning some skills such as cooking and hair-dressing which
prepares them for when they are finally leave from the Center.
</P>
<P>
It was in the center that Wen learnt to cook. 
</P>
</TEXT>
