<DOCNO> XIE20000626.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Archaeology News: Weekly Briefs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The following is a round-up of
China's archaeology news for the past week:
</P>
<P>
-- Ancient Exotic Casket Discovered in North China
</P>
<P>
Chinese archaeologists recently found a white marble outer
casket dating back some 1,400 years, which is considered to belong
to ancient Central Asian cultures.
</P>
<P>
The outer casket dates back to the Sui Dynasty (581-618) and is
the first of its kind ever discovered in China. Chinese
archaeologists unearthed the two-meter-high and 2.96-meter-long
white marble outer casket when excavating a tomb in Wangguocun
Village, Jinyuan District in Taiyuan, capital city of north China'
s Shanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
-- Four World Heritage Sites in China Certified by UNESCO
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural
Organization (UNESCO), has issued World Heritage Certificates to
four Chinese sites.
</P>
<P>
The four sites are Wuyi Mountain in east China's Fujian
Province, Dazu Stone Carvings in Chongqing Municipality in the
southwest, the Summer Palace and the Temple of Heaven in Beijing.
They were listed as world heritage sites by UNESCO in 1998 and
1999.
</P>
<P>
-- Ruins of Qijia Culture Discovered in Qinghai
</P>
<P>
Chinese archaeologists have discovered a site of Qijia Culture
in northwest China's Qinghai Province.
</P>
<P>
The Qijia Culture flourished in the transition period from the
Neolithic Age to the Bronze Age, some 3,500 to 4,000 years ago,
according to the Qinghai Provincial Archaeological Research
Institute.
</P>
<P>
The ruins are located in Lajia Village, Minhe County, on the
upper reaches of the Yellow River, believed to be the first of its
kind ever found in China.
</P>
<P>
-- Ancient Palace Found Underground
</P>
<P>
The main structure of a palace belonging to a Marquis during
the Han Dynasty (206 BC-220 AD), was confirmed by archeologists to
be located under an amusement park for children in the capital of
Guangdong Province in south China.
</P>
<P>
According to government officials, the amusement park and some
local residents will be displaced to make way for the project.
Relocation costs are estimated to be one billion yuan (120 million
U.S. dollars).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000626.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Archaeology News: Weekly Briefs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- Souvenirs on Dunhuang Grottoes Issued
</P>
<P>
A group of crystal souvenir items featuring the frescos and
sculptured figures of the Mogao Grottoes of Dunhuang, northwest
China's Gansu Province, were recently issued.
</P>
<P>
The souvenirs were to commemorate the centennial discovery of
the Sutras Cave and 100th anniversary of the establishment of
Dunhuang Studies this year.
</P>
<P>
-- Cliff Inscriptions Discovered in East China
</P>
<P>
Chinese archeologists have found two ancient inscriptions
carved on cliffs on Mount Yushan near the city of Changshu in east
China's Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
The inscriptions, believed to have been carved during the Song
Dynasty (960-1297), were found by a team of archaeologists from
the Changshu Museum and Suzhou Museum in a dense forest.
</P>
<P>
According to the Changshu archives, the mountain has a number
of historic heritage sites.
</P>
<P>
-- Repair of Ancient City Wall Completed
</P>
<P>
An eight-year-project to repair the eastern gate tower of the
city wall built during the Ming Dynasty (1368-1644) in Xi'an,
northwest China's Shaanxi Province, has been completed.
</P>
<P>
The 48,000-U.S. dollar project recovered the original styles
and features of the ancient city wall when it was built more than
600 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Xi'an, the capital of 12 dynasties in the Chinese history, has
3,000 historical sites. The 14-km-long ancient city wall is now
the best preserved city wall in the world.
</P>
<P>
-- Another Great Wall Ruin Opens To Visitors
</P>
<P>
A well-preserved section of the Great Wall at Shixiaguan in
suburban Beijing recently opened to visitors.
</P>
<P>
The Shixiaguan stretch of the wall is five kilometers southwest
of the famous Badaling portion, which has received up to 100
million visitors in the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
According to a local source, the little renovation of the
Shixiaguan section was done to highlight the original look of the
ruin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000626.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Reformist Majlis to Revise Conservative Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Speaker of the Iranian Majlis
(parliament) Mehdi Karrubi has indicated the legislative body is
determined to revise all laws that are old-fashioned or hindering
implementation of reform programs.
</P>
<P>
As agreed by the president and the judiciary branches of the
government, legislation which are old-fashioned, outdated or
irrelevant must be revised or amended, Karrubi was quoted by the
Islamic Republic News Agency as saying on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Karrubi, secretary-general of the Assembly of Combatant Clergy
and a close ally of reform-minded President Mohammad Khatami, was
elected speaker of the Majlis on June 11. The sixth Majlis,
dominated by reformers, started work on May 27.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with Secretary of the Guardians Council (GC) Ahmad
Jannati late Sunday, Karrubi also expressed hope that the Majlis
and the GC will cooperate well in the future. All legislation
passed by the Majlis has to be approved by the 12-member GC before
they can become laws.
</P>
<P>
In the meeting, Jannati expressed the hope that the new Majlis
will carry out its duties in the best possible way.
</P>
<P>
He also noted, however, that the Majlis does not have unlimited
authority and cannot solve all problems, hinting that the Majlis
has to be supervised and limited by bodies such as the GC and the
State Expediency Council, currently headed by former president
Hashemi Rafsanjani.
</P>
<P>
With reformers controlling the parliament, the Majlis and the GC
have actually become rivals. The conservative GC has for the past
months tried to block reformers from getting a upper hand in the
legislative body.
</P>
<P>
The parliamentary election in February resulted in a landslide
victory by the reformers, who ended the long-time conservative
dominance of the parliament. The victory is an important step for
the reformers toward seizing all powerful state organs of the
country, most of which are still under conservative control.
</P>
<P>
The powerful GC, supervisor of the elections, tried to save some
face for the conservatives by annulling election results in a
number of constituencies and transferring reformist victories to
the conservatives.
</P>
<P>
With severe pressure from the conservative establishment, the
new Majlis, however, managed to convene on May 27.
</P>
<P>
On June 18, the new Majlis passed a motion to review the press
law, which was amended by its conservative predecessor in the dying
days of its term to impose more restrictions on the reformist
press.
</P>
<P>
The motion indicated that reformers in the Majlis have taken the
first step toward carrying out their pledges of revising all old-
fashioned legislation and push forward the country's reform
programs advocated by President Khatami since he took office in
1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000626.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
