<DOCNO> XIE20000626.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Must Work Together to Ensure Sustainable Fisheries:  Singapore Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 26 (Xinhua) --ASEAN nations must work together
to ensure that fisheries are sustainable as a food source and a
foreign-exchange earner for the region, Singapore Minister for
National Development Mah Bow Tan said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
At the opening of the ASEAN Fisheries Federation (AFF) 10th
Council Meeting &AMP; Business Conference and the International
Coalition of Fisheries Association (ICFA) Annual Meeting, the
minister told the participants that new challenges call for a
concerted and determined effort from ASEAN's government agencies
and their private sector counterparts to ensure that fisheries in
the region are sustainable, environment-friendly and thriving so
that future generations continue to enjoy fish as a regular part
of their meal.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the pertinent challenges ASEAN nations must face
up to ensure long-term viability of ASEAN fisheries, Mah Bow Tan
listed the three thrusts to carefully manage fisheries resources,
practise environment-friendly aquaculture and reduce post-harvest
wastage.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that efforts must be made to balance the size of
catch with the need to ensure that available resources are not
harvested beyond their replacement rate.
</P>
<P>
"To over-fish and not allow the resources to regenerate
themselves posses a real threat which we cannot afford to ignore,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the importance to make environment-friendly
aquaculture industry mature into a major fish producer in ASEAN,
citing aquaculture production is estimated to reach 40 million
tonnes by 2010 and account for 30 percent of the total fish
production of about 140 million tonnes in the world.
</P>
<P>
He urged for more focus on fisheries post-harvest technology
to reduce post-harvest loss resulting from poor handling and
preservation and to achieve greater efficiency in the utilization
of fish catches.
</P>
<P>
Fish is an important source of protein for ASEAN's 500 million
people and ASEAN's total fish production in 1996 was over 13
million tonnes with 2.6 million tonnes or 15 percent produced by
aquaculture.
</P>
<P>
The trade in fish and fishery products is a big business for
ASEAN nations as their total exports in 1996 reached 7.7 billion U.
S. dollars or 14.7 percent of world exports and their imports
totaled 2.1 billion U.S. dollars, representing net foreign
exchange earnings of over 5 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In ASEAN there were about 1.7 million people involved in full-
time fishing activities and another three million people involved
in part-time fishing activities.
</P>
<P>
Singapore is one of the highest fish-consuming countries in
the region with per capita consumption at 26.8 kilograms yearly
and the nation's daily consumption at 60 tonnes of fishballs, fish
cake and other fish jelly products.
</P>
<P>
Local fish production, including aquaculture, only meets less
than 10 percent of Singapore's fish consumption and its trade in
fish and fishery products in 1998 was valued at one billion U.S.
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
