<HEADLINE> Explosion Injures One in Southern Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MANILA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- A young tailor was hurt when a
suspected homemade bomb exploded near him Sunday night in Davao
City in the southern Philippines, a police report reaching here
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the 18-year-old tailor sustained
shrapnel wounds on his head, face and legs, and was immediately
brought to the Davao Medical Center for treatment.
</P>
<P>
The bomb exploded around 7:45 p.m. near an electric post where
the tailor was waiting for a ride, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted witnesses as saying that two men on board a
public utility jeepney stopped at the scene prior to the incident.
</P>
<P>
One of them dropped by and left behind something near the
electric post and returned to their vehicle and got lost from the
area, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Police brushed aside speculations that it was a handiwork of
the separatist Moro Islamic Liberation Front rebels who warned
since last month to unleash a series of bomb attacks in the city.
</P>
<P>
The explosion followed after seven bombs exploded in nearby
General Santos City, killing a woman vendor and wounding 40 others
last Saturday evening. 
</P>
</TEXT>
