<HEADLINE> Cala-Azar Disease Kills 11 People in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The outbreak of Cala-Azar disease
has killed at least 11 people in Wajir District in northeastern
Kenya and 26 others were admitted into local hospitals, the Daily
Nation newspaper reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Cala-Azar is caused by parasites of the species Leishmani and
is spread by the sand fly, which is prevalent in areas of poor
nutrition.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed Ali, senior laboratory official in the district, said
another 200 people were infected following the outbreak of the
disease two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
The treatment of the disease takes 28 days and costs more than
20,000 shillings (about 260 U.S. dollars) a patient, Ali said.
</P>
<P>
A team of experts from the Ministry of Health and Kenya Medical
Research Institute had been sent to tour the district recently to
establish the extent of the disease.
</P>
<P>
Local officials also appealed to non-governmental organizations
and the government to put in place urgent measures to control the
spread of the disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
