<DOCNO> XIE20000626.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP Projects Improve Livelihood in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Africa 2000 Network
sponsored by the United Nations Development Program (UNDP) has
funded 82 projects worth 1.9 million U.S. dollars in Tanzania over
the past ten years, local newspapers reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Network's 1999 annual report issued here over the weekend
said that the projects have directly benefitted more than 250,000
persons.
</P>
<P>
The report said more than 200,000 people have enhanced their
environmental knowledge and awareness through programs and
projects supported by the network.
</P>
<P>
More than 80,000 people have got access to safe water. They
were also trained in sustainable management of water supply
systems. The rate of water-borne disease has gone down by 90
percent on average in the project- targeted areas, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, with the initiation of irrigation projects, food
supplies have more than doubled, ensuring food security for more
than 10,000 persons in those benefitted areas, the report added.
</P>
<P>
Tree planting and reforestation projects have regenerated
degraded land and more than one million trees have been planted in
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Small wild animals and some bird species, which had disappeared
some 30 years ago, are showing up again.
</P>
<P>
The objective of Africa 2000 Network Program is to financially
and technically support initiatives undertaken at the community
level as a part of sound natural resource management and food
security problem resolution.
</P>
<P>
It intervenes through community based organizations and NGOs in
12 African countries, which include Burkina Faso, Burundi,
Cameroon, Ghana, Kenya, Lesotho, Mauritania, Uganda, Rwanda,
Senegal, Tanzania and Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
