<DOCNO> XIE20000626.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Daily Air Quality Report for 42 Chinese Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Beijing, Shijiazhuang and Lanzhou
in north China reported level-three air pollution today with their
pollution indexes at 106, 107 and 106, respectively, the highest
among the 42 major cities monitored in the country, according to
the China Environmental Monitoring Center today.
</P>
<P>
Fairly good air was reported in Tianjin, Taiyuan, Hohhot,
Shenyang, Changchun, Harbin, Shanghai, Nanjing, Suzhou, Nantong,
Hangzhou, Wenzhou, Fuzhou, Jinan, Qingdao, Yantai, Zhengzhou,
Wuhan, Changsha, Zhanjiang, Chongqing, Xi'an, Xining, Yinchuan and
Urumqi.
</P>
<P>
All the 28 aforementioned cities listed particulates less than
10 microns in size as their major pollutants.
</P>
<P>
Dalian, Hefei, Xiamen, Nanchang, Guangzhou, Shenzhen, Zhuhai,
Shantou, Nanning, Haikou, Chengdu, Guiyang, Kunming and Lhasa
reported excellent air.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing reported sulfur dioxide as their major air pollutant.
</P>
<P>
The center classifies air quality in China's urban areas into
five levels: level-one or excellent (pollution indexes below 50),
level-two or fairly good (pollution indexes ranging from 51 to 100)
, level-three or slightly polluted (pollution indexes ranging from
101-200), level-four or poor (pollution indexes ranging from 201
to 300) and level-five or hazardous (pollution indexes over 301).
</P>
<P>
The 42 cities monitored include the four municipalities of
Beijing, Tianjin, Shanghai and Chongqing, provincial capitals, and
major cities in economically developed coastal areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
