<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Facing dissent within his cabinet over an upcoming Washington
summit and veiled threats from Palestinian National Authority
Chairman Yasser Arafat on a statehood declaration, Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak Sunday attempted to walk a tightrope in the
cabinet's first meeting since last week's political crisis.
</P>
<P>
Barak told his ministers that it is important to send out a
unified message in advance of the historic decisions.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister David Levy, however, expressed pessimism about
the negotiations and indicated the time is not ripe for a summit
when no progress is at hand.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli intelligence assessments hold that Iran is planning a
second test launch of its Shihab-3 surface-to-surface ballistic
missile in the coming weeks. The preparations under way in Iran for
the launching of the missile, whose range is estimated to be 1,300
kilometers, have aroused anxiety in Israel and the West.
</P>
<P>
Military intelligence stressed that the launch is of strategic
significance, not operational or tactical. Iran is believed to be
at least five years away from fitting a nuclear warhead to the
Shihab-3.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Interior Minister Natan Sharansky Sunday during a
weekly cabinet meeting proposed a shorter work week with a two-day
weekend. Sharansky, speaking during a discussion on the national
preferences for the 2001 budget, recommended introducing Sunday as
a day off in addition to Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the additional day of rest will help Israel
meet the challenges of globalization, suiting Israel to the
economic timetable of the global village. Prime Minister Ehud Barak
responded by saying it is an interesting proposal that will be
investigated.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak Sunday condemned a Saturday
arson attack on a conservative synagogue in Jerusalem as a "
horrible act that chills the souls of all Jews."
</P>
<P>
Eyewitnesses of the evening attack on the Ramot Forest
synagogue, in which windows were shattered and furniture destroyed,
said they saw a number of ultra-Orthodox people running away from
the site. No arrests have been made at this time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
