<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Quarter GDP Shows Slowing Economy in New Zealand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand economy slowed
significantly in the first quarter of this year, according to
official figures released here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Statistics New Zealand said gross domestic product (GDP), which
measures the total economic activity, grew by 0.8 percent in the
quarter, after recording a 2.3 percent rise in the fourth quarter
and a 2.6 percent lift in the third quarter of last year.
</P>
<P>
Despite the slowdown in activity during the first quarter, the
economy grew by 4.4 percent in the year from April 1999 to March
2000.
</P>
<P>
This compares with zero growth the previous year and was the
highest annual growth rate since 1995.
</P>
<P>
Growth this quarter was strongly influenced by exports, up 2.1
percent. For the whole year, New Zealand exports grew 6.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture and building activity recorded growth this quarter,
mainly on the back of good spring pasture growth and a surge in
new housing construction. However, the major contribution to the
increased activity came from the service industries, with the
largest contribution coming from increased activity in transport
and communications. The transport industry was buoyed in part by
record numbers of overseas visitors, up 8.9 percent in the first
quarter, compared with the same quarter a year ago.
Telecommunications continue to benefit from growing demand for
information technology-based products and services.
</P>
<P>
Business investment on fixed assets increased 1.6 percent this
quarter, following a 4.5 percent rise in the previous quarter. For
the year from April 1999 to March 2000, the increase was 7.8
percent, up markedly on the growth rates recorded in the previous
two years.
</P>
<P>
Latest surveys have shown sharp falls in business confidence
since March, which could rein in economic growth. Some local
economists predict growth for the second quarter of this year
could be as low as zero percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
