<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Parliamentary Election Result Won't Change Government Formation: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The ruling Zimbabwe African
National Union- Patriotic Front (Zanu-pf) will form the next
government whatever the outcome of the weekend parliamentary
elections would be, because the Constitution gives the President
power to appoint the Cabinet, Zanu-pf National Chairman John Nkomo
said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"We wish to make it clear that the media reports suggesting
that these elections might lead to a change of government are
more than wild," Nkomo told reporters at a press conference in
Harare.
</P>
<P>
"In terms of the Constitution, Zanu-pf will most definitely
form the next government whatever the results of the legislative
election," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Let's get it clear. President Robert Mugabe will form the
next government and this is something that has deliberately been
ignored or misrepresented by the media."
</P>
<P>
He said while the opposition might get some seats in the next
Parliament, no single opposition party had a chance of getting
anywhere near the two- thirds majority needed to push for some
Constitutional amendments.
</P>
<P>
The government had, through the Constitutional Commission, come
up with a home-grown draft constitution in February which entitled
the party commanding a majority in Parliament to name a Prime
Minister who would have a say in the appointment of Cabinet
ministers.
</P>
<P>
"We were quite pleased to come up with a home-grown
Constitution. That draft was very well arranged, but in terms of
the Lancaster House Constitution the unfortunate provision is that
President Mugabe will form the next government," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Those who want to cry foul are the same people who mobilized
for the rejection of the draft Constitution. So in any case
there is no way they could raise the required two-thirds majority
to affect amendments to the Constitution," he said.
</P>
<P>
Nkomo said that the government would still be constitutional
and President Mugabe did not have to be compelled to include
anyone from the opposition.
</P>
<P>
"President Mugabe does not have to prepare to include the
opposition. The President will have the right to appoint people
into Cabinet. He can form a Cabinet of five if he wants," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"He does not have to source manpower from other parties. He
will have a sufficient number of Zanu-pf Parliamentarians from
which to appoint his Cabinet," he said.
</P>
<P>
The elections on Saturday and Sunday were to choose Members of
 Parliament only, and not the President whose term runs up to
2002, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000626.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Private Investment In Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 26 (Xinhua) -- More and more Shanghai residents
are turning to private investment for higher economic returns amid
continuous interest cuts from savings deposits.
</P>
<P>
Most people choose to invest in such areas as welfare lottery,
securities, education, philately. Others open their own businesses.
</P>
<P>
In order to gain higher yields from their investment than their
savings deposits, local people purchase new houses on loans while
renting old ones.
</P>
<P>
Cai Wenfang is one of the many examples. She invested some
money into her cousin's plantation garden. After three years, she
earned profits ten times more than from her savings deposits.
</P>
<P>
Cao Jianming is another example. He plans to use one percent of
his income to buy lottery tickets. "Whether the investment is
lucrative depends on your luck, but once you win a prize in a
lottery, yields are much higher than what you have originally put
in," he said.
</P>
<P>
Some people suggest investing in old people's homes. This will
not only alleviate the younger generation's burden in taking care
of their parents but can also create job opportunities for the
laid-off workers.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, some local and foreign enterprises have opened
franchise services in Shanghai. Shanghai Lianhua Co., Ltd., for
example, initiated a program to encourage people to run a
chainstore with 70,000 yuan investment.
</P>
<P>
However, experts warn that it is safer for the elderly to
retain their savings deposits rather than invest their money
because investment requires a certain level of know-how and
expertise.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
