<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Trade-related News (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Following are the highlights of
major trade-related news released by Xinhua over the past week (
June 19-25):
</P>
<P>
 Foreign Trade
</P>
<P>
--China approved 7,724 new overseas-funded enterprises from
January to May, an increase of 22.37 percent over the same period
last year, according to the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
These new enterprises have a total contractual overseas
investment of 18.252 billion U.S. dollars, up 25.63 percent.
Actual overseas investment stood at 12.762 billion U.S. dollars, 8.
21 percent lower than the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
-- The Shanghai-based China Shipping Corporation (CSCO) has
recently opened a new far east-U.S. shipping route. CSCO uses five
2,500-TEU container ships on the weekly shipping route docking at
ports of Shanghai, Los Angeles, via a port in Japan.
</P>
<P>
-- The Chinese government has decided to set up its first group
of 15 export processing zones nationwide on a trial basis, to
reform the country's existing processing trade administration
system.
</P>
<P>
The zones are to be built in the cities of Dalian, Tianjin,
Beijing and Shanghai, and the provinces of Shandong, Jiangsu,
Zhejiang, Fujian, Guangdong, Hubei, Sichuan and Jilin, according
to a source at the working conference on the country's export
processing zone.
</P>
<P>
-- The China Ocean Shipping Group (COSG) Wednesday launched a
container freight shipping line between the port city of
Lianyungang in east China and Los Angeles on the west coast of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
This is the second container line between China and the U.S.,
following the inauguration of the first line between Qingdao in
east China's Shangdong province and the east coast of the US
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese President Jiang Zemin met Wednesday with Louis
Gerstner, chairman of board of directors and president of the
International Business Machines Corp. (IBM), and all the IBM board
members.
</P>
<P>
-- China's exports will slow down in the second half of this
year while imports are expected to increase quickly, Long Guoqiang
with the Development Research Center of the State Council said,
noting that the high rate of increase in exports in the first half
was based on a comparatively low base last year, and the growth
rate is expected to slow down in July.
</P>
</TEXT>
