<HEADLINE> Vietnam Intensifies Anti-Drug Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Senior Vietnamese officials and
thousands of university students attended an anti-drug gathering
here Sunday, marking the "International Day Against Drug Abuse and
Trafficking" which falls on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Pham The Duyet, member of the standing committee of the
Political Bureau of the Communist Party of Vietnam, made a speech
at the gathering, praising young people for launching an
intensified campaign against drugs and calling for departments of
all levels to fully cooperate in the nationwide campaign.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics released by Vietnamese authorities,
more than 100,000 drug addicts are registered in the country, of
whom 70 percent are young people.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, more than 500 young people from Hanoi joined the
publicity campaign by cycling around the city. Anti-drug
activities were also held in other cities.
</P>
<P>
A rally was held in Ho Chi Minh City, the biggest city in
Vietnam, attended by more than 3,500 Communist Youth Union members,
who declared, "the youth of Ho Chi Minh City are determined to
free the city of drugs."
</P>
<P>
The Ho Chi Minh Communist Youth Union has carried out various
kinds of activities to raise the awareness of the young people
about the harms drugs could do to them. Rehabilitation centers
have also been set up.
</P>
<P>
The number of drug addicts has been growing in Vietnam in
recent years. More than half of them and drug-related criminals
are reported in Hanoi and Ho Chi Minh City. 
</P>
</TEXT>
