<DOCNO> XIE20000626.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Food Adulteration Pervasive in Nepal: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 26 (Xinhua) -- There is a widespread practice
of adulteration of food in Nepal that badly affects the interests
of consumers, according to a survey released here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Adulteration amounts to 47.7 percent in sweets, 22 percent in
snacks, 74 percent in titoura (Nepalese food made of pulse flour)
and 32 percent in noodles, said a survey conducted by the Royal
Nepal Academy of Science and Technology (RONAST).
</P>
<P>
The survey said there are widespread cases of adulterating milk
with water and soda starch, ghee with vegetables and fat, honey
with sugar, dry tea with wood dust, edible oil with mineral oil
and chemicals, sugar with chalk powder, among others.
</P>
<P>
The survey found that delivering under-weight commodities for
the full price is considered clever by businessmen instead of
feeling guilty at violating the law.
</P>
<P>
It has become a tradition to extract some quantity from a sack
or a package containing designated quantities before selling the
sack or package, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
The survey attributed lack of effective implementation of the
Consumer Interest Protection Act as the main cause behind the
adulteration.
</P>
<P>
Since the fines imposed on those involved in adulteration and
selling commodities under weight are low, the practices are not
deterred.
</P>
<P>
Besides, as only one food inspector is available for 1.2
million people in Nepal and half of the inspectors reside in the
capital, it is difficult to detect cases of adulteration, the
survey said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
