<HEADLINE> Hyundai Motor, DaimlerChrysler Establish Alliance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Hyundai Motor and DaimlerChrysler
Monday announced that they have formed an alliance and will
establish a 50-50 commercial vehicle joint venture.
</P>
<P>
Hyundai Motor Chairman Chung Mong-koo announced the alliance
along with Dieter Zetche, DaimlerChrysler's president of
commercial vehicle production and responsible for Asia-Latin
American operations.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement between the two auto manufacturers, in the
alliance, DaimlerChrysler will acquire a 10 percent stake in
Hyundai Motor for 480 billion won (some 428 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The alliance will help their bid in the five-party competition
for merging ailing Daewoo Motor, which is capable of producing 2
million vehicles per year.
</P>
<P>
Now, General Motors, Ford Motor, DaimlerChrysler, Fiat and
Hyundai are competing to win the bid for Daewoo Motor. It is said
that General Motors and Fiat have formed a joint bid for Daewoo
Motor.
</P>
<P>
Whoever wins the bid will be given a strong foothold on the
growth car market in Asia, a key to the supremacy of the world's
industry, said analysts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
