<DOCNO> XIE20000626.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of Health News in China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The following are the highlights
of major news on health care and medical research in China over
the past week:
</P>
<P>
 Diabetes Website Launched in Beijing
</P>
<P>
A website dedicated to diabetes-related information was
launched last Tuesday in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Logging onto www.tang-an.com.cn or www.diabetes-china.com,
Internet surfers can get the latest information about diabetes
prevention, therapies and medical research. They can also enjoy
online purchase of certain medicines and health-promotion products.
</P>
<P>
 Study Shows Buckwheat-rich Diet Effective in Diabetes
</P>
<P>
 Control
</P>
<P>
A study made by Chinese researchers showed that eating
buckwheat-rich food can dramatically reduce the risk of
hyperglycemia and diabetes.
</P>
<P>
The average blood sugar level of people who eat buckwheat as
staple food is 3.9 millimole per liter, compared with 4.56
millimole per liter among the people who don't eat buckwheat,
revealed the study made among some 1,000 residents in Inner
Mongolia, one of China's major buckwheat production bases, by the
researchers at Harbin Medical University .
</P>
<P>
 Seminar on Health Sector Reform Held in Beijing
</P>
<P>
Government officials and health policy experts from China and
several international organizations held a seminar in Beijing late
last week to discuss reform and development strategies for China's
health sector in the first decade of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Participants of the Senior Policy Seminar on China's Health
Sector Reform and Development Strategies focused on topics such as
relationship between the health sector and social and economic
development, the role of the government and the market in health
development, management of health care organizations, and health
problems and solutions in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
 China Vows to Curb Radioactive-related Accidents
</P>
<P>
China's Ministry of Health announced last Friday that it will
organize a nationwide inspection of radioactive sources late in
the year, to prevent radioactive-related accidents from occurring.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics released by the ministry, China
reported 159 radioactive incidences between 1994 and 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000626.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of Health News in China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ministry of Health plans to carry out an inspection nationwide
this year focusing on small and medium-sized businesses that are
occupational hazards and have poor work environment facilities.
</P>
<P>
Statistics released by the ministry showed that 218 work-
related poisoning cases were reported last year, in which 759
people died or fell in ill, a rise of 15 percent and a rise of 47
percent respectively over the figures in 1998.
</P>
<P>
 Museum On Medicine Resources to Be Built
</P>
<P>
Southwest China's Guizhou Province plans to build a museum on
medicine resources in its capital city of Guiyang.
</P>
<P>
The museum will have nine exhibition halls covering 6,170
square meters and will mainly exhibit traditional Chinese medicine.
The museum will also collect and exhibit traditional medicines
from various ethnic groups in China.
</P>
<P>
 Tibet to Host International Symposium on Tibetan
</P>
<P>
 Medicine
</P>
<P>
An international symposium on Tibetan medicine will be held on
July 15-17 in Lhasa, capital of the Tibet Autonomous Region. It
will be the first of this kind ever held in the homeland of the 1,
300-year-old unique system of medical research, clinical practice
and drug use.
</P>
<P>
More than 360 Chinese and foreign researchers of Tibetan
medicine have applied for participating the symposium, providing
some 500 papers for academic exchange.
</P>
<P>
 Sino-Dutch Health Project Launched
</P>
<P>
China and the Netherlands have started a community health care
project in Qingdao, a port city in Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
In the next three years, experts sent by the Dutch government
will help Qingdao train medical professionals. By the year 2003
the city will have 100 doctors and 100 nurses, as well as 400
epidemic prevention and 400 maternity and child health personnel.
</P>
<P>
 Six Ethnic Gene Banks Established in Northeast China
</P>
<P>
Six ethnic gene banks have been established in northeast China'
s Harbin Medical University, in which the genes of six ethnic
minority groups including the Mongolian and the Xibo are currently
frozen in liquefied nitrogen at minus 273 degrees Celsius,
awaiting for deciphering.
</P>
<P>
The gene banks are set up to preserve genes of the ethnic
minority groups so that scientists may have the opportunity to get
to know the secrets behind some special anti-disease genes in such
ethnic groups and find a cure for such diseases someday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
