<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death Toll Rises to 52 in Communal Clash in Ambon, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The death toll in Wednesday's
fresh communal clash in Ambon, capital of Indonesia's Maluku
province, rose to 52 and the number of people wounded to 200,
according to national newspapers here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Fresh communal clashes between Christians and Muslims broke out
in Tantui village, Ambon, on Wednesday after two unidentified men
attacked three people. The clashes have spread to three other
villages.
</P>
<P>
Bloody street battles are reported to have raged again in the
city of Ambon, about 2,300 kilometers northeast of Jakarta, on
Sunday, killing at least 14 people and causing thousands to flee
to the mountains or to Halong Naval Base, 12 kilometers east of
Ambon.
</P>
<P>
A police housing complex and detention center in Perigilima, as
well as dozens of houses and a church were burned to the ground.
</P>
<P>
As of Sunday night, gunfire and explosions were still being
heard in several parts of the city.
</P>
<P>
"We are terrified as calls of war against Christians have been
broadcast through mosques," a local resident was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
A local Catholic priest Agus Ulayana told the Jakarta Post that
the situation had simply gotten worse.
</P>
<P>
"Everything is paralyzed here (Ambon), communications have been
cut and no transportation is available," Agus said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Indonesian Navy Sunday detained 10 Maluku
traditional ships carrying assembled machine guns, sharp weapons
and poisonous arrows heading for Maluku islands.
</P>
<P>
"The Navy succeeded in confiscating assembled long and short
machine guns, sharp weapons, ammunition and other sharp objects
from the ships," Chief of the Eastern Fleet Command Admiral Adi
Hariyoso was quoted by the Indonesian Observer as saying.
</P>
<P>
The government on Friday slapped a travel ban to Maluku islands
in a bid to stem violent communal clashes that have claimed more
than 2,500 lives since they erupted in January 1999.
</P>
<P>
In Jakarta, Chairman of the People's Consultative Assembly
Amien Rais Sunday supported the imposition of civil emergency law
in Ambon in a bid to halt the communal clashes.
</P>
<P>
He added the bloody unrest in Ambon is already more than enough
because it has been going on for almost two years.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian Military (TNI) Commander Admiral Widodo A.S. also
expressed support to such measure, and pledged TNI would take
stiffer measures in handling the unrest in Maluku.
</P>
<P>
However, Chairman of the Maluku legislative assembly Zeth
Sahuberua Sunday said there was no plan to declare a state of
civil emergency in the riot-torn provinces of Maluku and North
Maluku. 
</P>
</TEXT>
