<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Cracks Down on Drugs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China's coastal provinces and regions are on the alert for
syndicated drug trafficking, in addition to launching anti-drug
educational campaigns.
</P>
<P>
The Tibet Autonomous Region, which has witnessed a rising
number of drug addicts, from fewer than ten in 1992 to the present
1,500, has intensified its campaign against drug smuggling gangs
since May 10. Police arrested 53 suspected smugglers and seized 77.
9 grams of drugs.
</P>
<P>
Police in Tibet dealt with 58 drug-related cases in the first
half of this year, which is more than the total number of last
year.
</P>
<P>
The region has stepped up efforts to spread anti-drug
information, especially among young people.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan Province, which is adjacent to the notorious drug-
growing center known as the "Golden Triangle" in Myanmar,
uncovered the biggest case of drug smuggling in a human body last
month.
</P>
<P>
Chen Wanzhong, a member of a syndicated drug smuggling gang,
was apprehended as he attempted to carry across the border 530
grams of drugs in his body cavities. So far, border police have
arrested all 11 members of the gang.
</P>
<P>
The neighboring Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, known as
China's leader in the drug crackdown, recently burned 1,429 grams
of drugs in face of the public.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Mingpu, vice chairman of the Regional government, said
that the most urgent task of China's anti-drug campaign is to
better educate the public. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
