<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Capelle Wins French Cycling Championship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Veteran cyclist Christophe Capelle
won a mass sprint finish to lift the French championship crown and
his first individual title here Sunday, according to an AFP report.
</P>
<P>
The BigMat rider, an Olympic gold medal winner in the team
pursuit event at the 1996 Atlanta Games, beat former French
champion Jacky Durand and Anthony Morin to the post following the
243.1km run, AFP said.
</P>
<P>
The 32-year-old veteran was pleased with his performance
despite the effects of jet lag.
</P>
<P>
"I didn't feel very strong during the day. Last week I competed
in a World Cup track event in Mexico and I didn't feel well over
the past few days because of the time difference," Capelle was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless 1993 and 1994 French champion Durand had no answer
for the in-form Capelle who launched his attack aided by teammate
Guillaume Auger in the final kilometer of the race through western
France.
</P>
<P>
"I had great legs but I fell behind Capelle who was faster than
me," said 33-year-old Durand.
</P>
<P>
Capelle clocked five hours, 20 minutes and 44 seconds along
with a leading pack of some 31 riders.
</P>
<P>
However, the newly crowned French champion will not be
competing in the Tour de France from July 1-23 as his team did not
qualify.
</P>
<P>
"At BigMat Auber we're very disappointed not to be competing in
the Tour. I said this to Jean-Marie Leblanc (Tour de France
director). But that's life," added Capelle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
