<DOCNO> XIE20000626.0349 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Government Survives First Test of Confidence Since Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak's government easily defeated a no-confidence motion in the
Knesset (Parliament) Monday evening, a sign that it has pulled
through the political crisis in the past weeks.
</P>
<P>
The voting of the motion, submitted by the major opposition
Likud party over Barak's alleged "intention to transfer the Jordan
Valley to the Palestinians," was 19 for, 56 against, with six
abstentions, according to Israel Radio reports.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Barak agreed to transfer most of the Jordan
valley to the Palestinians in the recent talks. However, Barak had
stated that such media speculations were "inaccurate."
</P>
<P>
As expected, the ultra-orthodox religious Shas party, the major
rebellious ruling partner in Barak's coalition in the past few
weeks, ordered its Knesset members to vote with the government.
</P>
<P>
Shas, which threatened to quit the coalition, agreed to stay in
the government after reached an agreement with Barak's One Israel
bloc at the last minute on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement satisfied most of its demands, including funding
allocations for its ailing education network, legalizing its pirate
radio stations, having a say in the peace process with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The support of Shas, which has 17 seats in the 120-member
Knesset, for the government made Likud's no-confidence motion
virtually destined to failure.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Shas also helped the government to
block an early-election bill in Knesset's Constitution, Law and
Justice Committee Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
The parliamentary panel decided to recommend to the Knesset
plenary the dismissal of the bill calling for the dissolution of
Knesset, which passed its preliminary reading earlier in the month
with the help of then rebellious Shas.
</P>
<P>
Two votes from Shas members in the committee were pivotal, as
the recommendation was approved by a majority of eight to six.
</P>
<P>
The bill, proposed by Avigdor Lieberman from National Union-
Yisrael Beiteinu to dissolve the 15th Knesset and hold early
elections, passed its preliminary reading by a vote of 61-48 in the
Knesset on June 7.
</P>
<P>
The Knesset plenary reportedly will discuss the bill on Tuesday
or Wednesday to give its final decision on the bill.
</P>
<P>
According to Israeli law, if the bill is dismissed, the
oppositions should wait at least six months before tabling a
similar one asking for early elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
