<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Intefada on the Way if Peace Talks Fail, Arafat Warns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RAMALLAH, West Bank, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat threatened on Tuesday that the Palestinian people
will take up the intefada (popular uprising) again if a peace
agreement with Israel is not reached by September 13.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Xinhua in his office in Ramallah,
the West Bank, Arafat said if the deadline of September 13 passes
without a peace accord, he would walk out of Palestinian
territories and let the Israeli government to "talk directly with
his people."
</P>
<P>
"I have told U.S. President Bill Clinton not long ago that if
the peace talks with Israel fail, the Palestinian people will
return to the intefada" to gain their legal rights, Arafat said.
</P>
<P>
September 13 is the target date for a final peace agreement
between Israel and the Palestinians settling the thorniest issues
such as the status of Jerusalem, the Jewish settlements, borders,
water resources distribution and the fate of millions of
Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
A senior Palestinian official said earlier on Monday that if the
intefada emerged this time, "a blood river will run through the
Palestinian territories."
</P>
<P>
Arafat said the Palestinian people have the right to declare an
independent state any time after September 13, but the timing will
be decided at the Palestinian Central Council meeting on July 2-3
in Gaza.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader said Sunday that he would declare
Palestinian statehood within weeks.
</P>
<P>
Arafat also emphasized that he would "reject any attempt to
postpone the negotiations of the permanent status of Palestine" and
leave some issues unsolved this year.
</P>
<P>
Israel has proposed to seal a partial framework accord with the
Palestinians and leave some of the toughest issues for future
discussions, such as the status of Jerusalem and Palestinian
refugees' right to returning to their homeland.
</P>
<P>
On his upcoming meeting with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, Arafat said they would mainly discuss the implementation
of Sharm el Sheikh memorandum signed last September.
</P>
<P>
Albright arrives in the Middle East region on Tuesday in a bid
to breathe life into the stalled peace process and narrow the gap
between the Palestinian and Israeli sides for a summit meeting in
Washington between Arafat, Clinton and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak.
</P>
<P>
"At the moment, we have not decided when or whether to hold a
trilateral summit meeting" which aims to reach a framework
agreement as soon as possible, Arafat said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
