he is not criminally accountable for the incident, his political
responsibilities have obliged him to resign.
</P>
<P>
It is not immediately known whether Emir Sheikh Jaber Al-Ahmed
Al-Sabah has accepted the resignation. (Kuwait-Oil Minister-
Resignation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Head of the Justice Department of Iran's southern Fars
Province Hossein Ali Amiri said on Monday that the 13 Iranian Jews
accused of espionage for Israel will not face the death penalty,
and the final verdict for them is expected on July 1.
</P>
<P>
The defendants are only accused of "acts against the national
security" and the charge of "mohareb" (waging war against God and
the country) has been dropped, hence they would not face the
capital punishment, the official announced, actually repeating what
he said last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
His remarks contradict those of Prosecutor-General Ayatollah
Morteza Moghtadai who said on Sunday that the accused may receive
the death penalty since they have confessed to spying for Israel.
(Iran-Jews-Espionage)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
RAMALLAH, West Bank, -- Visiting U.S. Middle East envoy Dennis
Ross said here Monday there is a lot of work going on and more
might be done before a three-way American, Israeli and Palestinian
summit for Mideast peace.
</P>
<P>
After an hour-and-a-half meeting with Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat, Ross, who came back to the Middle East on Thursday for
another round of shuttling diplomacy, told reporters that there is
potential for such a summit to take place.
</P>
<P>
Ross' trip is aimed at preparing for the regional tour by U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, which is to begin on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Albright will try to judge whether the Israeli and Palestinian
positions on the main issues are close enough for the holding of
the summit between Arafat, U.S. President Bill Clinton and Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak next month in the United States.
(Palestine-Arafat-Ross)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanese President Emile Lahoud on Monday hold
unprecedented face-to-face talks with Hassan Nasrallah,secretary
general of the guerrilla group Hezbollah, in the wake of Israeli
troop withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Lahoud highly praised the sacrifice of Hezbollah in its fighting
against Israelis occupation, and stressed that Lebanon will never
abandon a single inch of its territory.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah, or Party of God, is a Shiite Muslim militant group
backed by Iran and Syria in spearheading a war of attrition that
drove out the Israeli occupation forces. (Lebanon-Hezbollah)
