<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The following are the economic briefs
from the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- The current annual production of cement in Iran, which
is among the 20 major cement producing countries in the world, is
28 million tons, and the figure is expected to rise to 34 million
tons in 2002, industrial sources said.
</P>
<P>
Over 1.85 million tons of cement were exported during the past
Iranian year that ended on March 19.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Dubai Internet City (DIC) announced Monday that it
had issued licences to more than 100 companies to set up their
business in the city.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed Al Gargawi, general director of Dubai Technology, E-
commerce and Media Free Zone Authority, said at a press conference
that most of the authorized companies have expressed their
commitments to invest in e-commerce, internet and programming
projects at the DIC.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the DIC administration is currently considering over
350 applications, he added.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The Bores Bozcaada Wind Energy Station was inaugurated
in Canakkale Province in Western Turkey on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The wind power station, which was built at a cost of 13 million
U.S. dollar, was constructed jointly with the German Enercon
Company. It is capable of producing 30 million kilowatt-hours
(kWhs) of electricity annually.
</P>
<P>
The project was conducted in the BOT (build-operate-transfer)
model and will be transferred to Turkey in the year 2020.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- A foundation stone was laid for the Can Thermic Power
Station in Canakkale Province on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The 400-million-dollar power station will start operation in 34
months with a capacity of 2.5 billion kWhs a year. 
</P>
