<HEADLINE> Bush Suggests Split of Immigration Agency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- U.S. presumptive Republican
presidential candidate George W. Bush Monday suggested that the
Immigration and Naturalization Service (INS) be split into two
agencies to woo the Latino voters in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Texas governor told the League of United Latin American
Citizens that by splitting the INS into two, one agency will
welcome new immigrants and another will strictly enforce the
nation's borders.
</P>
<P>
"It's an agency that sends mixed signals to the people we're
trying to help," Bush said in a speech to an audience of about 600.
</P>
<P>
"We ought to be saying loud and clear to people that the INS is
to help families and to help people understand the maze of rules
and regulations," he added.
</P>
<P>
Bush also promised to lift the ban on the visit of the spouses
and minor children of legal permanent residents while their own
entry applications are being processed.
</P>
<P>
Latino voters are expected to play an important role in the
November presidential election in the country. 
</P>
