<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian, Greek Presidents Drive Bilateral Ties Forward </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Vladimir Putin
and his Greek counterpart, Konstantinos Stephanopoulos, Monday
discussed here bilateral ties, international and regional issues
of common concern, pledging to advance bilateral cooperation to a
new level.
</P>
<P>
During the over-two-hour meeting in the Kremlin, the presidents
discussed in detail bilateral relations, and problems of
international security, including issues of combating
international terrorism, the situation in the Balkans, Putin told
journalists after the talks.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also mulled ways to expand cooperation in the
fields of military technology and energy, especially in the gas
industry and the construction of electrical plants, he said.
</P>
<P>
The European direction of Russia's foreign policy is "one of
our priorities, and in that respect, our relations with Greece
have particular importance," he said, describing the development
of bilateral ties in latest years as "positive and effective."
</P>
<P>
"Russia and Greece are brought together not only by their
spiritual and cultural links, we also have evolved the same or
similar opinions and stands on a number of international issues of
late," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Putin said the prospects for the two countries' economic
relations are good although a certain decline in bilateral trade
was witnessed over the past 18 months as a result of the recent
world crisis, which dealt a heavy blow on Russia.
</P>
<P>
"We maintain a very good relationship. There are no problems
between Russia and Greece, but only questions that need to be
discussed and solved together," said Stephanopoulos in reply, who
arrived in Moscow Sunday for an official visit, also the first
visit by a Greek president to Russia since 1993.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that both nations see broad potential for
strengthening bilateral interaction, which is developing
inspiringly.
</P>
<P>
On the Kosovo problem, Putin said the Balkan crisis should be
solved according to United Nations Security Council Resolution
1244.
</P>
<P>
He reaffirmed Russia's support for Yugoslavia's territorial
integrity and called for involving the Yugoslav leadership in
solving the Kosovo problem.
</P>
<P>
"It is necessary to seek the full demilitarization of Kosovo
and the disarmament of the Kosovo Albanian army. All existing
problems should be settled proceeding from the norms of
international law," he stressed, welcoming Greece's proposal to
settle some of the disputes in legal form.
</P>
<P>
The Greek president told the joint news conference that Athens
"takes most seriously Russia's proposal for creating a pan-
European anti-missile system." He expressed the hope that such an
important matter would be settled on the basis of cooperation and
the mutual understanding of all interested countries.
</P>
<P>
At the end of Monday's summit, the two countries' foreign
ministers signed a convention on avoiding double taxation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000626.0356 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Underlines Cooperation and Equality in World Disarmament Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 26 (Xinhua) -- China said here Monday that
the cooperation on an equal footing is essential for progress in
international disarmament efforts.
</P>
<P>
Shen Guofang, deputy Chinese permanent representative to the
United Nations, told the plenary meeting of the United Nations
Disarmament Commission (UNDC) that "the Chinese delegation
maintains that cooperation on an equal footing is essential for
progress in international disarmament efforts. This has been true
in the past and will remain so in the future."
</P>
<P>
"This is also an important part of the new security concept
advocated by China, which is based on mutual trust, mutual benefit,
equality and cooperation," he said.
</P>
<P>
"All countries, big or small, rich or poor, strong or weak,
should have an equal right to security," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Disarmament is not intended to enhance the security of an
individual country or a group of countries," he said. "Disarmament
should not become a tool for stronger nations to control weak ones,
still less should it be an instrument for a handful of countries
to optimize their armament in order to seek unilateral security
advantage."
</P>
<P>
"To carry out cooperation in the field of disarmament, all
countries should accommodate each other's security concerns and to
abandon unilateralism and hegemonism," he said. "Some countries
pursue the doctrine of 'mine is mine, yours is negotiable', and
frequently impose economic sanctions on other countries under the
pretext of nonproliferation."
</P>
<P>
"Such an approach is by no means desirable," he said.
</P>
<P>
"In the framework of collective security, enhancement of
international cooperation and common efforts offer the only
correct and effective way to address the proliferation of weapons
of mass destruction," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Such cooperation also requires all nations to respect and
abide by international arms control and disarmament instruments,
and to abandon cynicism in this area," he said.
</P>
<P>
"A certain state asks others to fulfill treaty obligations,
while keeping freedom of action for itself," he said. "When
ratifying a treaty, it adopted domestic legislation in violation
of the purposes of the treaty."
</P>
<P>
"It even threatened to withdraw from a treaty under groundless
pretexts," he said. "Such are demonstrations of hegemonism and
double standard, which will undermine international disarmament
efforts."
</P>
<P>
"China has always attached importance to the UNDC, and has
participated in its every session in a constructive manner," he
said. "The Chinese delegation holds the view that the UNDC plays
an irreplaceable role in formulating guidelines for international
arms control and disarmament."
</P>
<P>
"Under current circumstances when international disarmament
efforts have come to a crossroads, we need the UNDC even more to
explore principles and ways to advance the disarmament process,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
The plenary session was presided over by the UNDC chairman,
Javad Zarif, who is currently Iran's deputy foreign minister.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000626.0357 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
