<HEADLINE> N.Irish Protestant Parade Banned From Catholic Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland authorities Monday
banned the Protestant Orange Order from marching through a Roman
Catholic neighborhood when it stages a parade in the flashpoint
Drumcree area on July 2.
</P>
<P>
A Reuters report quoted the Parades Commission as saying in
Belfast, the capital city of Northern Ireland, that it had imposed
the ban to avoid a "risk of disorder" in the area some 40 miles (
65 kilometers) southwest of Belfast.
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday, scuffles broke out during an Orange Order march
in west Belfast and an angry Catholic crowd hurled bottles and
bricks at police. A senior Catholic republican politician was
slightly injured.
</P>
<P>
The Parades Commission said it could not allow this Sunday's
parade to go along the Catholic Garvaghy Road as the Orangemen had
proposed.
</P>
<P>
"A parade along the Garvaghy Road... risks being interpreted as
a deliberate attempt to raise tension," it said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Northern Ireland's majority Protestants hold the parades to
celebrate ancient battlefield victories. They anger Catholics who
regard them as triumphalist.
</P>
<P>
The Orange Order was not available for comment on the
commission's ban but it has condemned similar decisions in recent
weeks. 
</P>
