<HEADLINE> U.S. FAA to Provide Ground Safety System for 25 Airports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The decision to purchase the equipment was announced by FAA
Administrator Jane Garvey at the opening of a three-day airport
safety conference.
</P>
<P>
The system, called ASDE-X, is designed to give air traffic
controllers information about the location of planes and vehicles
at night and in bad weather when visibility is limited.
</P>
<P>
ASDE-X is similar to the ASDE-3 ground surveillance radar now
providing similar data to controllers at the 34 busiest airports
in the United States. The new units will provide added protection
to 25 smaller, less busy fields, the FAA said.
</P>
<P>
The 34 busiest airports are scheduled to be upgraded by 2002 to
a more complex system that will provide warnings of potential
collisions in addition to informing controllers of the locations
of aircraft and vehicles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
