<DOCNO> XIE20000626.0368 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: U.S. B2B Non-Service Spending to Soar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The volume of Internet
business-to-business in the United States is expected to grow 20-
fold over the next five years, opening the doors for new business
models such as Net markets and coalition markets, according to a
study released Monday.
</P>
<P>
More than 6 trillion U.S. dollars in online B2B trade is
expected by 2005, representing 42 percent of total U.S. B2B non-
service spending, according to the study by Jupiter Research, an
American research company specializing in Internet commerce. The
research defines online B2B trade as any sale made by business to
a business where either the terms of the transaction are agreed
upon online, or the majority of terms or item features are
configured online.
</P>
<P>
The research found that Internet B2B trade in the year 2000
will represent only 3 percent of the total U.S. B2B non-service
market, or 336 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the direct channel, the commerce of one seller to
many buyers, dominates 92 percent of the Internet B2B market. In
2005, however, 35 percent of the Internet B2B trade volume will be
conducted via a Net market, a matching up of many buyers and many
sellers, or through a coalition market, which comprises a
consortium of buyers or sellers, according to Jupiter.
</P>
<P>
The value proposition of the Internet is on a grander scale for
the B2B space; the sheer size of B2B trade, coupled with
inefficient process, makes the Internet migration of business
strategies very attractive to companies, the study found.
</P>
<P>
"Over the next several years, businesses will face an array of
new opportunities to improve and expand their sales and
procurement processes," Jupiter said. "They must invest now, even
though the payoff will take some time; it will require several
years to see a substantial migration from today's manual, paper-
based solutions to tomorrow's Internet purchasing counter."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000626.0369 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
