<HEADLINE> Drug Dealings Increase in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Zambia has experienced an increase
in drug dealings despite the stringent measures by the government
to combat the problem, according to a senior official.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's Home Affairs Minister Peter Machungwa said on
Monday the Drug Enforcement Commission (DEC) had arrested 8,695
drug dealers in the last 10 years when officiating celebrations to
mark this year's National Day Against Drugs in Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
The year 1999 alone accounted for a total of 1,867 arrests of
drug dealers and a seizure of narcotic drugs with a street value
of 6 billion kwacha (about 2 million U.S. dollars), he said.
</P>
<P>
He called on the DEC to continue with its program of
disseminating drug- related information to schools, colleges and
the community in order to enable young people to resist
temptations to take drugs.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the same occasion, DEC Commissioner Raphael Mungole
urged the government to fund his organization adequately if it was
to fight the drug scourge in the country effectively.
</P>
<P>
He added that the arrest of 930 drug traffickers and seizure of
narcotic drugs with a street value of 3.4 billion kwacha (about
1.1 million dollars) on June 25 this year was an indication that
the DEC was committed in tackling the drug problem in Zambia.
</P>
</TEXT>
