<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia to Develop Irrigation to Feed Population </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- A senior Ethiopian official
emphasized here Monday that Ethiopia had no alternative but
develop irrigation agriculture to produce sufficient food for its
population.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening of the Nile 2002 Conference, Water
Resources Minister Shiferaw Jarso said Ethiopia can not hope to
feed its ever growing population with the kind of its present
farming method, which continues to depend on rain.
</P>
<P>
"It is because of our dependence on rain-fed agriculture that
we have repeatedly faced serious food shortages, and sometimes
famine", he said.
</P>
<P>
"There is no alternative for us except developing small, medium
and large scale irrigation schemes in order to secure adequate
food and create employment for the millions of rural population",
Shiferaw said.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, about 10 million Ethiopians have
been in need of food aid because of crop failure as a result of
erratic rains during the past three consecutive seasons.
</P>
<P>
"It is the Ethiopian government's policy that irrigation
development will be carried out alongside hydro-power development
without causing significant negative impact to the co-basin
users," he said.
</P>
<P>
The eighth Nile 2002 conference is sponsored by the Canadian
International Development Agency, the United Nations Development
Program, the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United
Nations and the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
It is aimed at encouraging discussion to foster cooperation
among the Nile riparian countries. The four-day meeting is being
attended by about 400 experts for the Nile riparian countries.
</P>
<P>
The 6,500 kilometer-long Nile, which is one of the longest
rivers in the world, runs across 10 countries. Despite
contributing 86 per cent of the water to the river, Ethiopia uses
a very small amount of the Nile resources.
</P>
<P>
Monday's sessions discussed country papers on policy nature,
and research papers on the social and environmental aspects of
developments of the Nile.
</P>
<P>
In the coming three days, the participants will also
deliberate, among others, on development priorities and management
of the Nile countries, solidarity and peace building among the
countries, the organizers said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
