<HEADLINE> U.S. Opposes Lifting of Sanctions on Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. State Department said
on Monday that it opposes the lifting of U.N. sanctions against
Sudan until that country takes verifiable steps to end its support
for terrorism.
</P>
<P>
"In terms of the sanctions position, we do not support the
lifting of sanctions until the government of Sudan takes concrete,
verifiable steps to end its support for terrorist groups,"
spokesman Philip Reeker said in response to questions about recent
contacts between the U.S. and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
"This is a direct reflection of the U.N. Security Council
Resolutions 1044, 1054 and 1070, which set specific requirements,
which Sudan has not fulfilled," he added.
</P>
<P>
Reeker said that Sudan has so far failed to turn over or
accounted for the suspects in a 1995 assassination attempt on the
life of Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, and to take convincing
steps to end its support for terrorist groups.
</P>
<P>
As to U.S. special envoy Harry Johnston's recent trip to
Khartoum from June 12th to 14th, Reeker said that Johnston was
there to strengthen the Sudan peace process and to urge increase
access for humanitarian supplies.
</P>
<P>
The Organization of African Unity has reportedly urged the
Security Council to rescind sanctions imposed in 1996 after Egypt
accused Sudan of sheltering Moslem militants who tried to
assassinate President Mubarak in Addis Ababa a year earlier.
</P>
</TEXT>
