<HEADLINE> U.N. Calls for Concerted Efforts against Drug Trafficking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Observing the International Day Against Drug Abuse and Illicit
Trafficking which falls on June 26, U.N. General Assembly
President Theo-Ben Gurirab said drugs are produced in both
industrialized and developing countries and in the rapidly
globalizing world, no country is immune of the drug menace.
</P>
<P>
In his message, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan warned that
the huge sums of money generated by drug trafficking "fuels a
culture of corruption and violence which tears at the fabric of
civil society".
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need to prevent drug abuse before it starts, as
drug trafficking responds to demand.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the head of the U.N. Drug Control Program Pino
Arlacchi told journalist in New York that the internet was growing
more important as a means of exchanging information on how to
expand the illicit drug market and how to manufacture or find
illicit substances.
</P>
<P>
The International Day was observed against a backdrop of
growing drug menace. Wealth of today's worldwide illicit drug
trade is estimated at 400 billion U.S. dollars annually, according
to statistics of the United States where illegal drugs cost 110
billion dollars and claim 52,000 lives a year. 
</P>
