<HEADLINE> Survey Predicts Continued Volatility in U.S. Equity Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street's top economists
and strategists predict that the U.S. market volatility recently
seen will continue over the next five years and forecast a sharp
decline in U.S. equity market returns, said a report released
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. equity market is expected to return 9.1 percent
annualized over the next five years, dramatically below the 23
percent return over the last five years, according to a global
survey of 66 leading international investment institutions
conducted by KPMG LLP, the U.S. member firm of KPMG International
and professional service firm.
</P>
<P>
Double-digit returns are expected in specific asset classes
such as venture capital, international small cap-equities,
emerging market equities, small-cap equities, emerging market
bonds and international equities. For all other asset classes,
including global equities, large-cap equities, convertibles, real
estate, bonds and treasury bills, survey respondents forecast
single-digit returns.
</P>
<P>
The survey indicates respondents expect venture capital
investments to provide the greatest return of any asset class over
five years, at 15.2 percent, followed by international small-cap
equities at 13.1 percent and emerging markets at 13 percent. The
only other asset groups expected to yield double-digit returns
over five years are U.S. small-cap equities with 12.4 percent,
emerging-market bonds with 10.6 percent and international equities
with a return of 10.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
"This is a clear indication that there is strong macroeconomic
support for a return to developing markets overseas as well as a
continuing rebound from the currency turmoil that ravaged the
markets in 1997," KPMG said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
