<HEADLINE> Chirac: German-Franco Axis Ensures European Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
 BERLIN, June 26 (Xinhua)--Visiting French President Jacques
Chirac Monday evening said the European integration would succeed
only when its German-Franco motor well functioned.
</P>
<P>
While giving a speech on the future of Europe to students at
Humboldt University, Berlin, Chirac urged Germany and France to co-
operate more closely for the future of Europe.
</P>
<P>
"The further building-up of Europe, to which there is no
alternative, will succeed only when the German-Franco motor
functions well," said Chirac.
</P>
<P>
The road of European integration has met with a turning point,
"now the choice is necessary, and it can be painful to us all," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Chirac praised a May speech by German Foreign Minister Joschka
Fischer, who blueprinted a "European Federation." That vision is
an "intelligent option," said Chirac.
</P>
<P>
Fischer indicated in that speech a European constitution, a
bicameral parliament and a central government.
</P>
<P>
But presently the initiative of a "European Central Government
" has gone too far, said Chirac, "that will be totally
unacceptable to some member countries."
</P>
<P>
Every member in the future Europe will keep its identity and
nations will not disappear, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Chirac reaffirmed what he told a Sunday television interview,
that a "European common constitutional framework" should be
drafted in two years.
</P>
<P>
The French President also urged the European youth to devote
to European integration.
</P>
<P>
"Never be skeptical, but be engaged in the construction of
Europe," he said, adding that the future Europe should not only
secure the democracy in every member country, but also create a "
European model" in social issues.
</P>
<P>
Chirac also indicated three-lingual courses in European
education system. "The European children should learn to speak two
foreign languages as early as possible," he said.
</P>
<P>
Chirac, the first French President to pay a state visit to
Germany in 13 years, arrived in Berlin Monday noon, when German
President Johannes Rau greeted him with military ceremony in front
of his presidential palace.
</P>
<P>
Germany and France do not always share same opinion on
European integration. Deferent voices were heard when Rau said he
preferred a "European Charta" to Chirac's "European Constitution."
</P>
<P>
While giving speech at the state banquet for Chirac, Rau said
deferent laws in EU member countries should remain, and it was "on
the false way" to manage the total continent with a common basic
law.
</P>
<P>
There should be a "European Charta" to clearly divide the
powers of the European Union and its member countries, said Rau.
</P>
<P>
"The civil rights can be ensured in the way that only the most
needed are decided on European level," said Rau.
</P>
<P>
Before his trip to Berlin, the Chirac family had toured around
the Expo 2000 world fair in Hanover under the guidance of German
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Chirac is due to give a speech in the Reichstag
building to depict more clearly his vision of Europe, which will
highlight his three-day visit to Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
