<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Solana Urges Reinforced Cooperation in EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The European Union's High
Representative for Foreign and Security Policy, Spain's Javier
Solana, said here on Monday that reinforced cooperation in the EU
will be debated and decided before the end of the year at the
Inter-Government Conference to reform EU institutions in view of
enlargement.
</P>
<P>
The former NATO secretary general, who met the press after
taking part in a book presentation, also said that the problem of
illegal immigration today is being tackled by individual Member
State governments but it was beginning to become an EU question.
</P>
<P>
While in Rome, the EU's foreign and security policy chief was
slated to meet with Italian President Carlo Azeglio Ciampi,
Premier Giuliano Amato and Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini, who
also attended the presentation of the book on national interests.
</P>
<P>
In regards to the IGC, Solana observed that "reinforced
cooperation" has officially been put in the agenda and thus will
be "debated and decided upon during the French EU presidency",
from July to December 31.
</P>
<P>
"It is a very important decision," he added, "because at the
European Council in Helsinki, which opened the IGC, reinforced
cooperation was not on the agenda but now it is on the IGC agenda".
</P>
<P>
Reinforced cooperation allows EU members to move ahead on their
own in certain areas. The decision to place it on the IGC agenda
was made during the Portuguese EU presidency, which expires on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini said here Monday that
the introduction of a mechanism to allow for "reinforced
cooperation" in the European Union is fundamental and thus the
failure of the Inter-Governmental conference to reform EU
institutions would be"unthinkable". 
</P>
</TEXT>
