<HEADLINE> Mexico's Food Dependence with US Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
From 1990 to 1999, meat exports from United States to Mexico
went up from 86 to 90 percent, and of prepared meat from 62 to 95
percent, said specialists in their report "NAFTA's Impact on the
Horticultural Sector ".
</P>
<P>
Mexico, United States and Canada hold in force since 1994 NAFTA
with an over 400 million inhabitant market.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, in sweeteners and sugar, United States
increased its sending to Mexico from 29 to 95 percent, from 1990
to 1999, and rice's from 29 to 95 percent.
</P>
<P>
Different nations have been sent off Mexico's market due to the
increase of the presence of American products in face of tariff
advantages derived from NAFTA, the document said .
</P>
<P>
United States displaced meat producers Australia and New
Zealand for Mexico, Italy and France in prepared meats, Chile in
fruits and Asian nations in rice, according to experts.
</P>
<P>
Mexico closed 1999 with a deficit in the agrofood balance of
775 million dollars, with imports for 5.622 billion dollars over
exports for 4.947 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Mexico's farming and fishing exports went up almost 70 percent
from 1994 to 1999, and imports 24.5 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
